"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671666","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-16","<p>At Autumn Statement, the Government confirmed that reform of the off-payroll working rules in the public sector will be implemented on 6 April 2017. Draft legislation and a technical note which explains the changes was published on 5 December and is available at: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/off-payroll-working-in-the-public-sector-reform-of-the-intermediaries-legislation-technical-note/off-payroll-working-in-the-public-sector-reform-of-the-intermediaries-legislation-technical-note</p><p> </p><p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is currently consulting on the draft legislation. The consultation period closes on 1 February.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC is also working with stakeholders to develop and test the new digital employment status service, which will help customers apply the off-payroll rules, making them simpler to administer. HMRC expects to provide a full version of the service for April 2017, but customers may be able to access this earlier.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-01-16T16:09:16.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671666/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671666/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671666/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-11","Self-Employed: Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress has been made on implementing recent changes to legislation on IR35 with regard to intermediaries.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","59515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671667","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-16","<p>UK consumers already benefit from a high quality financial advice market. The Retail Distribution Review Post Implementation Review found that the quality and independence of financial advice has improved significantly. It was found to have reduced conflicts of interest arising from commission payments and improved professionalism and competition.</p><p> </p><p>The problem is that this advice can sometimes be unaffordable. That is why the Financial Advice Market Review (FAMR) recommended a package of measures to make financial advice more affordable. The Government is making good progress in implementing its findings. As recommended by FAMR, the Government consulted on introducing a Pensions Advice Allowance, which will allow people to withdraw £500 tax free from their pension pot early, to pay for retirement advice. The Government will respond to the consultation shortly. A £500 tax exemption for employer arranged pensions advice will also be available from April 2017.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-01-16T10:23:47.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671667/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671667/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671667/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-11","Retirement: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress has been made under the terms of the Financial Advice Market Review on improving the quality of advice being offered to people preparing for retirement.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","59518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671668","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-19","<p>Business rates are based on valuations from the Valuation Office Agency and we do not intervene in their independent assessments. We have put in place a £3.6 billion transitional relief scheme for England to ensure no ratepayers are unfairly penalised at the 2017 revaluation.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-19T16:36:04.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671668/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671668/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671668/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671668/answer/previousversion/29875","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-11","Solar Power: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential impact of business rate rises on the British solar industry; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","59513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671669","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-18","<p>Government is committed to supporting the delivery of affordable housing and ensuring the housing market works for everyone.</p><p> </p><p>Over 300,000 affordable homes have been delivered since 2010. However, the scale of the challenge requires us to go further, which is why my RHF the Chancellor announced in the Autumn Statement that Government will invest an additional £5.3bn in housing. This includes £1.4bn funding to deliver 40,000 new affordable homes across England.</p><p> </p><p>In December, government also announced the launch of a new £60m fund to help around 150 councils tackle the problem of high levels of second home ownership in their communities. The fund will allow local groups to deliver affordable housing aimed at first time buyers. The South West will receive almost £20m through the fund.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-01-18T14:28:29.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671669/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671669/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671669/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-11","Affordable Housing: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what fiscal steps he is taking to increase the affordable housing supply in the South West.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","59520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671670","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-16","<p>I set out the nature of the guarantees which the UK Government has committed to in my answer of 7 October 2016. The Barnett formula has never had any role with regard to the determination of EU funding. As such, the Barnett formula has no role in determining the levels of funding which we have committed to covering through those guarantees.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-01-16T13:46:58.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671670/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671670/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671670/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-11","Public Expenditure: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 7 October 2016 to Question 46769, on Public Expenditure: Wales, whether that matched funding will be paid via the Barnett formula.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","59541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671671","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-16","<p>The government has guaranteed all multi-year European Structural and Investment Fund (ESIF) projects which are signed ahead of the point at which the UK leaves the EU. Funding for projects will be guaranteed if the department responsible for managing the relevant ESIF programme is satisfied that projects provide strong value for money and are in line with their strategic priorities. Each government department will take responsibility for the allocation of money to projects in line with these conditions and the wider rules on public spending.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-01-16T13:46:01.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671671/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671671/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671671/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-11","EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the Government's domestic strategic priorities are in relation to its guarantee for all European Structural and Investment Fund projects signed after the Autumn Statement 2016 and before the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","59570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671672","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-16","<p>The government has provided a guarantee for all European Structural and Investment Fund projects signed before the UK’s departure from the European Union. This includes projects that will continue beyond the UK’s departure from the European Union. The government has said that it will consult closely with stakeholders to review all EU funding schemes in the round, to ensure that any ongoing funding commitments best serve the UK‘s national interest, while ensuring appropriate investor certainty. The Government will continue to consider how best to support our regions following the UK’s departure from the European Union.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-01-16T13:43:47.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671672/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671672/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671672/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-11","EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will take steps to establish a programme of social and regional development funding to replace the European Structural and Investment Fund after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","59571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671673","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-16","<p>Leaving the EU means we will want to take our own decisions about how to deliver the policy objectives previously targeted by EU funding.</p><p>We will consult closely with stakeholders, including the Scottish Government, to review all EU funding schemes in the round, to ensure that any ongoing funding commitments best serve the UK‘s national interest.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-01-16T13:48:58.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671673/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671673/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671673/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-11","EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of the loss of European Structural and Investment Funds after the UK leaves the EU on (a) economic growth, (b) output, (c) productivity and (d) employment in (i) Glasgow, (ii) Scotland and (iii) the UK.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","59572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671674","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-16","<p>The accelerated payment regime was introduced in Finance Act 2014 to change the underlying economics of tax avoidance by requiring disputed tax to be paid upfront while an avoidance scheme is being challenged. Disputed tax remains due and payable under the accelerated payment regime until such time as the dispute is settled by agreement with HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) or the dispute is litigated and there is a judicial decision.</p><p> </p><p>Where an accelerated payment has been made, it is repayable if HMRC agrees, or the courts decide, that the scheme in question does produce a tax advantage under the legislation.</p><p> </p><p>Taxpayers can make representations to HMRC about an accelerated payment notice if they believe the conditions for issue have not been met or the amount shown is incorrect. They can also ask the courts to judicially review the issue of an accelerated payment notice.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","59587 ; 59588","2017-01-16T17:26:18.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671674/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671674/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671674/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-11","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if HM Revenue and Customs will make it its policy not to use accelerated payment notices when court proceedings relating to a case remain open.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker","59586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671675","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-16","<p>I replied to the Rt Hon Member's letter on 16 January.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-16T17:34:32.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671675/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671675/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671675/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-11","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to respond to the letter from the hon. Member for Walsall North of 13 December 2016 on the funding for supported housing consultation.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","59573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671676","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-30","<p>Government is clear that local planning authorities must work together to plan for common strategic interests. However, we have heard concerns about the effectiveness of the duty to co-operate. The Local Plans Expert Group in particular raised the difficulties that some areas have in providing for the housing they need within their own boundaries. Through the Neighbourhood Planning Bill, we said that we want to see more collaboration by authorities to address issues that require solutions across geographical boundaries.</p><p>We continue to consider options to ensure authorities effectively collaborate on common strategic issues and will be publishing a Housing White Paper shortly.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-30T17:30:57.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671676/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671676/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671676/answer","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671676/answer/previousversion/30238","Biography information for Lord Barwell","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-11","Local Plans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the duty to cooperate in the development of local plans.","false","Biography information for Mims Davies","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","59560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671677","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-18","<p>If a freeholder is unhappy with the services provided by a management company they can, with their neighbours, collectively approach the company and ask it to sell the freehold of any communal areas. This is a matter of negotiation between both interested parties. There are currently no plans to allow a right in law for freeholders to enforce a purchase. We will continue to monitor the situation.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-18T17:32:56.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671677/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671677/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671677/answer","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671677/answer/previousversion/29863","Biography information for Lord Barwell","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-11","Housing: Management","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will introduce legislative proposals to grant freeholders the right to remove property management companies from new developments.","false","Biography information for Gordon Henderson","Sittingbourne and Sheppey","Gordon Henderson","59534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671678","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-17","<p>We have consulted on future options for planning application fees. We will announce a way forward shortly.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-17T17:38:54.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671678/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671678/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671678/answer","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671678/answer/previousversion/29865","Biography information for Lord Barwell","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-11","Planning Permission: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans he has to allow local authorities to charge different rates to those set nationally for processing planning applications.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","59554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671679","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-17","<p>On 15 December we announced the second year of a four year settlement, which will provide Bristol City Council with over £1.3 billion to spend on local services between 2016-17 and 2019-20. As a democratically elected organisation, Bristol City Council is independent of central government and is responsible for managing its budget in line with local priorities. We are giving the council the funding it needs to plan responsibly.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-17T17:34:13.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671679/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671679/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671679/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671679/answer/previousversion/29867","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-11","Local Government Finance: Bristol","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make an assessment of the effect of recent changes to government funding to Bristol City Council on local council services in Bristol South constituency.","false","Biography information for Karin Smyth","Bristol South","Karin Smyth","59512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671680","Department for Education","false","2017-01-19","<p>The table below shows estimated funding for adult skills budget English for speakers of other languages (ESOL) provision from 2009/10 onwards, and also includes funding by the Department for Communities and Local Government. We do not hold data before 2009/10.</p><p> </p><p>Funding for ESOL is allocated by the Skills Funding Agency as part of a provider’s adult skills budget. In addition, there are a number of ESOL courses funded through the Agency’s community learning budget, but we do not collect data which enables us to provide a breakdown of the expenditure on these. SFA-funded providers which deliver ESOL include Further Education colleges, local authorities and a few other providers</p><p> </p><p>From 2013/14 the Department for Communities and Local Government has directly funded six projects to engage isolated adults with poor or no English who had not previously accessed mainstream training.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>YEAR</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>DfE ACADEMIC YEAR</strong> <strong>ESTIMATED FUNDING*</strong> <strong>(Adult Skills Budget)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>DCLG FINANCIAL YEAR</strong> <strong>FUNDING FOR ENGLISH LANGUAGE PROJECTS</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>£203m</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>£169m</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>£117m</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>£128m</p></td><td><p>£0.12m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>£120m</p></td><td><p>£2.14m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>£104m</p></td><td><p>£3.66m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>£90m</p></td><td><p>£2.53m</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>*(Formerly the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills) – funding values are estimated using data from the Individualised Learner Record (ILR). Estimated funding provides an indication of the level of government funding and should not be treated as actual spend.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-01-19T13:27:54.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671680/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671680/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671680/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-11","English Language: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what information the Government holds on the amount of funding from the public purse which has been made available for lessons in English for speakers of other languages in constant prices in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","59503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671681","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-17","<p>Allocations from the New Homes Bonus to Peterborough City Council since 2011 are set out below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>New Homes Bonus Allocation</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>£1,112,997</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£2,303,400</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£3,438,807</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£4,743,491</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£6,335,270</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>£7,901,640</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-18 (provisional)</p></td><td><p>£6,547,501</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Figures in 2017/18 are provisional and will be confirmed once any representations on housing statistics submitted by local authorities have been considered.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-17T17:38:25.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671681/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671681/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671681/answer","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671681/answer/previousversion/30239","Biography information for Lord Barwell","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-11","Housing: Peterborough","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much New Homes Bonus funding Peterborough City Council has received in each year since 2011; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Stewart Jackson","Peterborough","Mr Stewart Jackson","59641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671682","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-26","<p>Business rates are based on valuations from the Valuation Office Agency and we do not intervene in their independent assessments. We have put in place a £3.6 billion transitional relief scheme for England to ensure no ratepayer is unfairly penalised at the 2017 revaluation.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","59611 ; 59612","2017-01-26T17:13:34.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671682/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671682/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671682/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671682/answer/previousversion/29868","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-11","Solar Power: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make it his policy to deem solar panels as excepted plant and machinery for the purposes of business rates in a similar way to gas-powered combined heat and power boilers.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","59610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671683","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-26","<p>Business rates are based on valuations from the Valuation Office Agency and we do not intervene in their independent assessments. We have put in place a £3.6 billion transitional relief scheme for England to ensure no ratepayer is unfairly penalised at the 2017 revaluation.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","59610 ; 59612","2017-01-26T17:13:34.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671683/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671683/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671683/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-11","Solar Power: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will take steps to ensure that proposed changes in business rates do not have an adverse effect on the solar industry.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","59611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671684","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-26","<p>Business rates are based on valuations from the Valuation Office Agency and we do not intervene in their independent assessments. We have put in place a £3.6 billion transitional relief scheme for England to ensure no ratepayer is unfairly penalised at the 2017 revaluation.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","59610 ; 59611","2017-01-26T17:13:34.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671684/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671684/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671684/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-11","Microgeneration: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make it his policy to make the microgeneration exemption from business rates permanent in order to assist companies in investing in clean energy.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","59612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671685","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Right to Buy campaign aims to ensure that eligible social housing tenants are aware of the increased discounts available through the Right to Buy scheme as well as changes to the scheme and that those who are interested in taking up this opportunity to be a home owner, know where to obtain the necessary information to help them decide if it is right for them.</p><p>The direct marketing activity sets out to raise awareness of and eligibility of Right to Buy as Right to Buy can only be exercised by eligible tenants if they know about it, can check their eligibility and have sufficient information about their Right to Buy.</p><p>For the last wave of marketing in October 2016, we sent leaflets to a combination of 789,695 households informing them of their legal Right to Buy their home. The Department spent the following:</p><p>1. Production/ Printing/ Postage: £75,116.60</p><p>2. Distribution/ Data purchase: £60,951.67</p><p>The direct marketing activity has driven a strong response over the last 4 years of the campaign with a conversion rate of around 8% which is significantly higher than industry norms and has also led to improved efficiencies in local authorities through generating higher quality applications– further evidence of value for money.</p><p>The cost of the production and distribution of the Direct Marketing equates to 18 pence per leaflet. Over 63,000 tenants have now been able to buy their homes since April 2012, generating £3.5 billion in additional sales receipts. There were 12,000 sales in 2015-16, nearly 5 times higher than pre-reinvigoration sales in 2011-12.</p><p>Under the reinvigorated Right to Buy, local authorities are now able to keep the receipts from additional Right to Buy sales to pay off debt and fund additional affordable housing.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-30T17:20:24.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671685/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671685/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671685/answer","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671685/answer/previousversion/29870","Biography information for Lord Barwell","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-11","Right to Buy Scheme: Publications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the cost to the public purse was of (a) producing and (b) distributing the Right to Buy information booklet to households.","false","Biography information for Meg Hillier","Hackney South and Shoreditch","Meg Hillier","59613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671686","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Right to Buy campaign aims to ensure that eligible social housing tenants are aware of the increased discounts available through the Right to Buy scheme.</p><p>The Direct Marketing activity sets out to raise awareness of the scheme and eligibility as Right to Buy can only be exercised by eligible tenants if they have sufficient information about their Right to Buy.</p><p>Direct marketing has been the most cost effective way to reach eligible council and housing association tenants.</p><p>Our targeting approach is based on a combination of social housing stock and penetration levels - we target higher stockholding areas to ensure reach and value for money across England.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-30T17:30:04.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671686/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671686/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671686/answer","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671686/answer/previousversion/29871","Biography information for Lord Barwell","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-11","Right to Buy Scheme: Publications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what criteria his Department used to decide where the  Right to Buy information booklet was distributed.","false","Biography information for Meg Hillier","Hackney South and Shoreditch","Meg Hillier","59614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671687","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-19","<p>Principal local authorities are required to calculate a basic amount of Band D council tax for their whole area. If special items or expenses are applied, an additional amount may be charged in some areas. Special items or expenses include parish precepts and the cost of meeting levies.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-19T16:37:04.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671687/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671687/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671687/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671687/answer/previousversion/30240","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-11","Council Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether principal local authorities have the ability to set different levels of Band D council tax for different parts of their local authority area; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","59687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671688","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-17","<p>We are proud to support the community pubs sector wherever possible. That is why we are co-funding the £3.6m More Than a Pub programme to support communities aspiring to own their local pubs. Yesterday I announced a further £50,000 for Pub is The Hub to help them to continue with their excellent work in helping pubs to provide an ever-expanding range of new community-focussed services and meaning that, since April 2013, we have provided Pub is the Hub with £320,000.</p><p>In addition the Government cut beer duty and scrapped the beer duty escalator in 2013, with beer duty then being cut again in successive budgets before being frozen at Budget 2016. The sector has stated this is a major factor in helping to stimulate growth.</p><p>We have also removed permitted development rights for the change of use or demolition of pubs the community has nominated as an Asset of Community Value. This allows for a local decision on any planning application and provides an opportunity for the community to comment on any proposals.</p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy",,"2017-01-17T17:45:43.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671688/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671688/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671688/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671688/answer/previousversion/29872","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-11","Community Assets: Public Houses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to support local community pubs.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","59655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671689","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-18","<p>The Adult Social Care Support Grant is a one-off grant available only in 2017-18. However next year councils will also be able to raise the adult social care precept earlier - by up to 3%, and 3% the year after (2018/19), but by no more than 6% over the next three years. This could raise £200m in additional funding for adult social care in 2017-18 and over £400m in 2018-19. Councils will also be benefitting from the increased funding for the Better Care Fund, £105m in 2017-18, £825m in 2018-19 and £1.5bn in 2019-20. An explanation of the distribution of this funding can be found in the Local government finance settlement 2017-18: technical consultation –</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/553819/Post_Publication_-_Draft_Settlement_Summer_Consultation.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/553819/Post_Publication_-_Draft_Settlement_Summer_Consultation.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-18T17:37:45.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671689/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671689/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671689/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671689/answer/previousversion/30241","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-11","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether the adult social care support grant will be allocated to local authorities for 2018-19 on a similar distribution to that of 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","59685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671690","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-17","<p>The figures are in the table below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Council tax arrears £000</p></td><td><p>Non-domestic rate arrears £000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bournemouth Borough Council</p></td><td><p>12,363</p></td><td><p>3,693</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Christchurch Borough Council</p></td><td><p>1,594</p></td><td><p>554</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Poole Borough Council</p></td><td><p>4,021</p></td><td><p>1,119</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Dorset District Council</p></td><td><p>2,019</p></td><td><p>709</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Please note that this is only the second time we have collected non-domestic rate arrears data so they must be regarded as experimental data and could be revised in subsequent data collections.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-17T17:33:23.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671690/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671690/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671690/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671690/answer/previousversion/30242","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-11","Council Tax and Non-domestic Rates: Dorset","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the level of (a) council tax arrears and (b) non-domestic rate arrears was on 31 March 2016 in (i) Bournemouth Borough Council, (ii) Christchurch Borough Council, (iii) Poole and (iv) East Dorset District Council.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","59686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671691","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-16","<p>Developing brownfield land continues to be a priority for Government. In 2015-16 there was a four per cent increase in the proportion of new residential addresses created on previously developed land to 61 per cent.</p><p>The Vacant Building Credit, which is part of Government policy on Section 106 planning obligations, was introduced to incentivise development on brownfield land and bringing empty buildings back into use. An independent review of Community Infrastructure Levy, including its relationship with Section 106 planning obligations, was commissioned by Government in 2015 and reported to Ministers in October 2016. Government is reviewing the recommendations of the review group and will make further announcements in due course.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-16T17:02:55.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671691/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671691/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671691/answer","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671691/answer/previousversion/29873","Biography information for Lord Barwell","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-11","Property Development: Derelict Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness of (a) the small sites exemption and (b) vacant building credit as part of planning policy in respect of developing new residential homes on brownfield land; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Stewart Jackson","Peterborough","Mr Stewart Jackson","59674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671693","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-19","<p>An application for a judicial review of the consultation exercise has been made. The government has given an undertaking to the court that it will not take any final decisions on the matters to which this consultation relates until the court has determined the judicial review application. We are unable to commit to a timetable at this time.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-01-19T12:38:28.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671693/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671693/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671693/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-11","Culture, Practices and Ethics of the Press Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Written Statement of 11 January 2017, HCWS401, within what timescale her Department plans to complete analysis of the responses to the consultation on the Leveson Inquiry and its implementation.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","59669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671695","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-18","<p>This is a matter for Ofcom. DCMS has noted Ofcom's competition and consumer assessment, as set out in its successive consultations on the forthcoming auction of 2.3 and 3.4 GHz spectrum.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-01-18T10:33:07.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671695/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671695/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671695/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-11","Mobile Phones: Radio Frequencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions her Department has had with Ofcom on introducing a 30 per cent cap on mobile spectrum.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","59670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671696","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Call for Evidence on the Review of Gaming Machines and Social Responsibility received 275 responses.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-01-16T13:14:16.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671696/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671696/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671696/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-11","Gaming Machines and Social Responsibility Measures Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many responses her Department received to the call for evidence on the Review of Gaming Machines and Social Responsibility Measures.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","59697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671697","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-17","<p>One of the three licensing objectives that underpin the regulation of gambling in Great Britain is that it must be conducted in a fair and open way.</p><p> </p><p>Earlier this month I wrote to the Gambling Commission to ask for their views on the application of Tattersalls Rule 4 deductions and I will consider the Commission’s response carefully.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-01-17T15:38:33.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671697/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671697/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671697/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-11","Horse Racing: Betting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions she has had with the Gambling Commission on the application of Tattersalls Rule 4 deductions.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","59583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671698","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-19","<p>Government remains committed to considering the results of the 2014 Impact Review on the 2001 UNESCO Convention on the Protection of Underwater Cultural Heritage, in order to assess whether the UK should pursue ratification. A decision on timescales for reviewing the Convention will be made in late Spring 2017. Government has already adopted the Rules for activities directed at underwater cultural heritage, found in the annex of the Convention, as best practice.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-01-19T17:04:42.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671698/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671698/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671698/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-11","Convention on the Protection of the Underwater Cultural Heritage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress has been made on ratifying the UNESCO Convention on the Protection of Underwater Heritage.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","59576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671699","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-17","<p>Defence Ministers and officials have had no recent meetings with National Defence Medal campaign groups.</p><p>For details of our position on this matter I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 14 December 2015 to Question 19127 to the hon. Member for Great Grimsby (Melanie Onn).</p><p>http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-12-08/19127/</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-01-17T16:11:50.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671699/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671699/answer","20151214_19127_WQnA_extract_on_Veterans_Military_Decorations.docx","19127 - WQnA extract on Veterans Military Medals","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671699/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-11","Veterans: Military Decorations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent meetings he has had with campaign groups on the potential introduction of the National Defence Medal to recognise the contribution of veterans.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","59502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671700","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-17","<p>The UK-US Memorandum of Understanding that enables interoperability of UK and US Reaper aircraft by both nations remains valid but has not been enacted since 10 March 2016.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-01-17T16:02:41.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671700/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671700/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671700/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-11","USA: Military Alliances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Answer of 10 March 2016 to Question 30085, on unmanned air vehicles: deployment, whether the UK-US Memorandum of Understanding remains valid; and whether the provisions of that Understanding have been enacted by either party since 10 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","59577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671701","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Ministry of Defence continues to progress the Type 31e General Purpose Frigate requirement. The programme is in its pre-concept phase.</p><p>This work is considering the capability the ships will need based on their role, operating environment and the threats they will need to counter.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-01-16T16:52:07.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671701/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671701/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671701/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-11","Frigates: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what progress has been made on the procurement of type 31E general purpose frigates; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","59637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671702","Department for Education","false","2017-01-19","<p>The information requested is not available. Destinations of students six months after leaving UK higher education are collected and published annually by the Higher Education Statistics Agency (HESA) as part of the Destination of Leavers from Higher Education (DLHE) survey. However, the location of residence of higher education leavers is not collected in the DLHE survey.</p><p>Latest statistics were published in June 2016 for students leaving their courses in the 2014/15 academic year and are available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.hesa.ac.uk/news/30-06-2016/sfr237-destinations-of-leavers" target="_blank">https://www.hesa.ac.uk/news/30-06-2016/sfr237-destinations-of-leavers</a></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-01-19T17:54:19.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671702/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671702/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671702/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-11","Overseas Students: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the number of EU (a) undergraduate and (b) graduate students who have remained in (i) Greater London, (ii) the London Borough of Newham and (iii) East Ham constituency after the end of their course in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","59625"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671703","Department for Education","false","2017-01-18","<p>Tuition fee loans and maintenance loans are available to undergraduate students for the full length of their courses, including those lasting for four years or more. Support available to those students with the lowest household incomes was increased by over 10% in the 2016/17 Academic Year.</p><p>Non-repayable support is also available to students with children or adult dependants, and to students with a disability or specific learning difficulty.</p><p>Widening participation in higher education remains a priority for this government. Entry rates to higher education for young people in the most disadvantaged groups have risen to the highest rates on record. The proportion of students from disadvantaged backgrounds entering higher education is up from 13.6% in 2009 to 18.5% in 2015. The latest data for entry in 2016 shows that the application rate for 18 year olds from disadvantaged backgrounds is at a record level.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-01-18T16:42:54.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671703/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671703/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671703/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-11","Higher Education: Working Class","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to provide financial support to working class students on degree courses which last longer than three years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","59626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671704","Department for Education","false","2017-01-16","<p>We do not collect data on the curriculum provision of individual schools, including the provision of sex education. Sex education is compulsory in all maintained secondary schools, and primary maintained schools and academies are encouraged to teach it as an important part of delivering a balanced curriculum.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-01-16T15:43:03.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671704/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671704/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671704/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-11","Sex and Relationship Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of (a) primary and (b) secondary school children attend a school where sex education is taught.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","59621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671705","Department for Education","false","2017-01-17","<p>The Department’s main measures of secondary school performance are now Progress 8, Attainment 8, Ebacc achievement and entry and pupils achieving a Good Pass in mathematics and English. Progress 8 will be used to identify schools beneath the floor. The latest statistics are available in the ‘GCSE and equivalent results: 2015 to 2016 (provisional) in England’ National Statistics release[1], although breakdowns by pupil characteristics including free school meals is not available until 19 January 2017.</p><p>The table below provides the information for the last three years:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="6"><p>Pupils known to be eligible for FSM achieving 5+ A*-C grade GCSEs</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p>2012/13</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>2013/14[2]</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>2014/15[3]</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Number</p></td><td><p>Percentage</p></td><td><p>Number</p></td><td><p>Percentage</p></td><td><p>Number</p></td><td><p>Percentage</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Selective schools</p></td><td><p>574</p></td><td><p>92.6</p></td><td><p>556</p></td><td><p>93.9</p></td><td><p>510</p></td><td><p>92.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>All state-funded mainstream schools</p></td><td><p>32,286</p></td><td><p>39.8</p></td><td><p>27,007</p></td><td><p>35.3</p></td><td><p>25,332</p></td><td><p>34.9</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/gcse-and-equivalent-results-2015-to-2016-provisional" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/gcse-and-equivalent-results-2015-to-2016-provisional</a></p><p>[2] In 2013/14, two major reforms were implemented which affect the calculation of key stage 4 performance measures data: 1) Professor Alison Wolf’s Review of Vocational Education recommendations which: restrict the qualifications counted; prevent any qualification from counting as larger than one GCSE; and cap the number of non-GCSEs included in performance measures at two per pupil, and 2) an early entry policy to only count a pupil’s first attempt at a qualification, in subjects counted in the English Baccalaureate. Consequently, the numbers supplied prior to 2013/14 are not comparable with those from 2013/14 onwards.</p><p>[3] In 2014/15, early entry policy, under which only a pupil’s first attempt at a qualification is counted in performance measures, was extended to all subjects.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-01-17T17:29:44.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671705/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671705/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671705/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-11","GCSE: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what (a) proportion  and (b) number of children eligible for free school meals who achieved five A to C grades at GCSE including English and mathematics in each of the last three years attended a (i) maintained and (ii) grammar school.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","59689"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671706","Department for Education","false","2017-01-17","<p>Since April 2010 local authorities have reported expenditure on children’s centres (combined with early years) through annual Section 251 returns. This information is published at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-local-authority-school-finance-data#local-authority-and-school-finance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-local-authority-school-finance-data#local-authority-and-school-finance</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/section-251-materials" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/section-251-materials</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Planned expenditure on early years provision in each local authority is published at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-local-authority-school-finance-data#planned-local-authority-and-school-spending-" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-local-authority-school-finance-data#planned-local-authority-and-school-spending-</a></p><p> </p><p>Early years expenditure was not separately recorded until 2013-14, therefore data is not available for 2010 to 2013. Prior to 2013-14, early years funding was part of the total dedicated schools grant allocated to each local authority.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-01-17T08:35:27.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671706/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671706/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671706/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-11","Pre-school Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the gross local authority expenditure was on Sure Start Children's Centres and early years provision in each local authority area in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","59688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671707","Department for Education","false","2017-01-17","<p>Improving teacher quality is vital to improving educational outcomes for pupils wherever they are in the country; high-quality teachers are the single most important factor determining how well pupils achieve in schools.</p><p> </p><p>At a national level we are retaining and recruiting the teachers we need. We recognise, however, that the strengthening economy and growth in pupil numbers have made the situation more challenging and that this is more acute in certain subjects and particular schools or areas of the country. We are therefore spending over £1.3bn in the five years to 2020 to attract high-quality new entrants to the profession; and we are actively addressing issues that lead teachers to consider leaving the profession, such as unnecessary workload and poor pupil behavior.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the recently published Northern Powerhouse Strategy, we will design, fund and test a range of approaches to attracting and retaining high-quality teachers in the North, including West Yorkshire. We will look to engage the regions and the sector as we work up plans. We will provide more details on this in spring 2017.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-01-17T17:26:13.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671707/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671707/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671707/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-11","Teachers: West Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to (a) attract and (b) retain newly-qualified teachers in (i) disadvantaged schools and (ii) deprived areas in West Yorkshire.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","59652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671709","Department for Education","false","2017-01-16","<p>We take the issue of witness anonymity extremely seriously.</p><p>The independent panel overseeing the teacher misconduct case of some of the individuals involved in the events related to Trojan Horse recently ordered the full disclosure of transcripts of interviews given to Peter Clarke. As a result of the independent panel’s direction, lawyers acting on behalf of NCTL wrote to witnesses to inform them of that decision, and stated that in the event that they had any comments or concerns in relation to the disclosure of their transcripts they should contact them. Since the direction, where we have written to witnesses and we have either not yet heard back from them or they have raised concerns, no disclosures have been made. We have informed the independent panel that a number of witnesses have raised concerns, and the panel has indicated that it wishes to consider the issue at a further hearing.</p><p>These issues are part of a set of complex legal proceedings and it would be inappropriate to comment further at this stage.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-01-16T17:38:57.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671709/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671709/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671709/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-11","Schools: Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, for what reasons a decision was taken to reveal the identities of whistleblowers in the Trojan Horse case in Birmingham; and what assessment her Department has made of the effect on the safety of those individuals and their families of that decision.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","59636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671710","Department for Education","false","2017-01-16","<p>In 2016, 69.3% of children achieved a good level of development as defined by the Early Years Foundation Stage statutory framework. Of the 30.7% of children who did not achieve a good level of development in 2016, 1.5% (3089 children) attended a PVI setting. The data to determine the number and proportion of children attending private and voluntary settings only is not readily available, and could only be compiled at a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The Profile is an assessment based on a teacher’s observations of each child in their reception year, and is designed to ensure that parents and Year 1 teachers are informed about their learning and development attainment. The Profile is not intended to hold providers to account.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-01-16T17:50:26.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671710/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671710/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671710/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-11","Pre-school Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of children not achieving a good level of development according to the Early Years Foundation State were attending a private or voluntary sector provider in the latest year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","59691"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671711","Department for Education","false","2017-01-17","<p>The data requested is published in Tables 14LA and 15LA of the ‘Provision for Children Under 5 years of age’ Statistical First Release: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/education-provision-children-under-5-years-of-age-january-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/education-provision-children-under-5-years-of-age-january-2016</a>.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-01-17T08:16:13.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671711/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671711/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671711/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-11","Pre-school Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many two, three and four year olds in state-funded 15 hours' early education are in settings which are rated (a) requires improvement and (b) inadequate.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","59690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671712","Department for Education","false","2017-01-16","<p>Supplementary funding for maintained nursery schools, worth £55m a year, will be provided to local authorities at least until the end of this Parliament. This will enable them to maintain the current levels of funding for these schools, which play an important role in the social mobility of the children and families that they serve.</p><p> </p><p>Indicative Early Years National Funding Formula allocations for local authorities for 2017-18 can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/early-years-national-funding-formula-allocations-and-guidance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/early-years-national-funding-formula-allocations-and-guidance</a></p><p> </p><p>To ensure that local authorities receive the correct funding for their nursery schools, we will be undertaking a data assurance exercise to verify current expenditure levels in those authorities with maintained nursery schools. Once this has been completed, we will update allocations for individual local authorities in early summer.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-01-16T17:50:45.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671712/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671712/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671712/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-11","Nurseries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much funding from the transitional protection for maintained nursery schools will each local authority area receive in each year for which that funding is available.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","59692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671713","Department for Education","false","2017-01-16","<p>Officials at the Department held a range of discussions with the A level exam boards on this issue as soon as AQA made clear that it did not intend to continue developing a new A level in archaeology. However, it is for individual examination boards to decide which qualifications to offer and we regret that no board has come forward that is willing to develop a new A level in archaeology for teaching from 2017.</p><p> </p><p>However, the option for an exam board to develop qualifications in this subject in future will remain open.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-01-16T17:03:59.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671713/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671713/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671713/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-11","Archaeology: GCE A-level","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions she has had with (a) AQA and (b) other examination boards on ensuring the continuance of A-level archaeology on the curriculum.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","59519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671714","Department for Education","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Government is considering the future of the un-commenced provisions in the Equality Act.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-01-16T17:51:18.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671714/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671714/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671714/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-11","Public Bodies: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will commence the socio-economic duty on public bodies contained within section 1 of the Equality Act 2010.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","59542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671715","Department for Education","false","2017-01-16","<p>We are not able to provide the information requested. However, the Office of National Statistics (ONS) publishes the UK gender pay gap figures annually. This measure includes all basic pay before deductions for PAYE, National Insurance, pension schemes, student loan repayments and voluntary deductions, but does not include benefits or tax credits:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Overall GPG</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>19.8%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>20.2%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>19.6%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>19.8%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>19.2%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>19.3%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>18.1%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>To close the gender pay gap, the Government is introducing mandatory reporting for large employers in Great Britain from April 2017.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-01-16T17:51:03.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671715/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671715/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671715/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-11","Personal Income: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what women's median income as a percentage of men's was from all sources including pay, pensions, benefits and tax credits for each year from 2010 to 2016.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","59540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671716","Department for Education","false","2017-01-18","<p>The Department for Education encourages high performing schools, including grammar schools, to sponsor weaker schools. Any organisation interested in becoming an academy sponsor must apply through a rigorous process that is decided by the relevant Regional Schools Commissioner on behalf of the Secretary of State.</p><p> </p><p>Further details can be found on the sponsorship section on the Department website - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/academy-sponsorship" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/academy-sponsorship</a>.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-01-18T13:34:55.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671716/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671716/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671716/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-11","Grammar Schools: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her Department's policy is on grammar schools in failing school improvement partnerships becoming academy sponsors of those schools.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","59546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671717","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-16","<p>The US authorities are conducting the necessary steps to formally lift their restrictions on exports of EU lamb to the US. Defra is working with the US authorities to ensure exports of lamb from the UK can commence as quickly as possible once the restrictions have been lifted.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-01-16T12:45:40.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671717/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671717/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671717/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-11","Sheep Meat: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to her Department's press release, Lamb exports to America closer, published on 27 July 2016, what information she holds on when the first Welsh lamb exports to the US are expected to take place.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Williams","Ceredigion","Mr Mark Williams","59639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671718","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-17","<p>The Departments work together closely to ensure flood risk is an important consideration in the planning system. Local planning authorities must have regard to the National Planning Policy Framework when preparing Local Plans. The Framework sets out strict tests to protect people and property from flooding which all local planning authorities are expected to follow. The Framework is clear that Local Plans should be supported by a Strategic Flood Risk Assessment and take account of flooding advice from the Environment Agency and Lead Local Flood Authorities.</p><p> </p><p>Local Plans are examined by a planning inspector who will assess whether a plan is sound, including whether it is consistent with national planning policy. A local authority can only adopt a Local Plan that has been found sound.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-17T10:36:17.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671718/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671718/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671718/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-11","Floods: Property Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department has taken with the Department for Communities and Local Government to ensure that local authorities take account of flooding issues when producing their local development plans.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","59651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671719","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-17","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply given to the hon. Member for Twickenham, Dr Tania Mathias, on 7 December 2016, PQ UIN 55985.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-17T15:44:38.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671719/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671719/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671719/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-11","Plastics: Packaging","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans her Department has to encourage large retailers to reduce excess plastic packaging of products bought (a) in retail stores and (b) online.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","59654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671720","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-17","<p>The Government favours a voluntary approach to the prevention of food waste, including the redistribution of surplus food to feed people. A law focused on the redistribution of surplus food from supermarkets would not resolve the barriers to redistribution. Research published by the Waste and Resources Action Programme in May 2016 indicates that supermarkets only produce around 200,000 tonnes of the 10 million tonnes of food waste which arise each year in the UK. Our approach is to work with the whole supply chain through the voluntary Courtauld 2025 agreement.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-17T15:40:53.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671720/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671720/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671720/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-11","Food: Waste","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment her Department has made of the feasibility of bringing forward legislative proposals to reduce the practice by large food retailers of destroying or disposing of unsold food.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","59653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671721","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-17","<p>The 5p charge on single use carrier bags was brought in for England in October 2015 and so far it has been highly effective at reducing consumption: early data suggests it will lead to six billion fewer plastic bags being issued in the first year of the charge (over seven billion carrier bags were issued by seven main retailers in 2014). The charge in England has also resulted in donations of more than £29 million from retailers towards good causes including charities and community groups.</p><p> </p><p>Any additional change in policy would require an assessment of cost and efficacy implications. The Single Use Carrier Bags Charges (England) Order 2015 requires the Secretary of State to carry out a review of this Order before 5 October 2020.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-17T10:30:47.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671721/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671721/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671721/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-11","Plastic Bags: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of charges for plastic carrier bags; and whether she has plans to increase the number of retailers who are required to levy those charges.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","59622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671722","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-16","<p>As at close of business 11 January, 45 out of 922 eligible farm businesses in the Westmorland and Lonsdale constituency have not received their Basic Payment Scheme 2016 payment.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-01-16T14:10:56.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671722/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671722/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671722/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-11","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many farmers in the South Lakeland local authority area have not received their 2016 basic payment scheme funding.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","59642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671723","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-17","<p>This Government remains committed to recycling and will be consulting widely on our plans for resources, waste and recycling in developing our 25 year environment plan engagement framework. We also continue to work with businesses, local authorities and waste managers on policies and initiatives to encourage recycling.</p><p> </p><p>Defra Ministers, officials and I have had a number of discussions with a range of stakeholders in drawing up our 25 year environmental plan and in developing ongoing policy; as part of these discussions, companies and representative trade organisations will raise issues and ideas about specific products or treatments.</p><p> </p><p>As part of our ongoing stakeholder engagement, Defra officials were involved in discussions regarding the development of the Paper Cup Recycling and Recovery Group Manifesto and attended its launch on 27 June 2016. This manifesto aims to significantly increase paper cup recycling rates by 2020 and includes coffee chain companies as signatories.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-17T15:46:39.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671723/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671723/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671723/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-11","Beverage Containers: Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions (a) she and (b) Ministers and officials of her Department have had with coffee chain companies on the disposal and recycling of take-away cups.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","59662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671724","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-17","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply given to the hon. Member for West Ham, Lyn Brown, on 9 September 2016, PQ UIN 44382.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-17T15:48:11.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671724/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671724/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671724/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-11","Beverage Containers: Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to improve recycling solutions for polyethylene-lined paper cups.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","59663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671725","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>The planned talks in Astana have not yet taken place. We hope that they can contribute to a UN-led process. The United Nations Secretary General’s Special Envoy for Syria has indicated a plan to hold UN-mediated talks in Geneva in February. The British Government will continue to support the work of the UN including through our role in the UN Security Council and in the International Syria Support Group.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-16T16:40:14.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671725/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671725/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671725/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Syria: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the Government intends to participate in future Syrian peace talks that build on those that were previously conducted in Astana.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","59638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671726","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>The UK Government’s longstanding policy on the Middle East peace process is well known. We support a negotiated settlement leading to a safe and secure Israel living alongside a viable and sovereign Palestinian state.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-16T16:28:53.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671726/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671726/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671726/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the Government's policy is in respect of the two-state solution for Israel and Palestine.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","59631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671727","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>Mr Shai Masot, who was notified to Her Majesty's Government as a member of the Israeli Embassy's administrative and technical staff, is exempt from UK immigration control.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-16T16:34:48.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671727/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671727/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671727/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Shai Masot","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the immigration status is of Shai Masot.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","59632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671728","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>We have received no reports about Russian interference in the affairs of the Government of Romania.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-19T16:49:26.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671728/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671728/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671728/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Russia: Romania","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on alleged Russian interference in the affairs of the government of Romania.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","59609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671729","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Government is very concerned about various reports that we have received of alleged Russian interference in the affairs of the government of Montenegro, including a coup plot on election day last October, and is working closely with partners on the issue.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-19T16:51:34.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671729/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671729/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671729/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Russia: Montenegro","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on alleged Russian interference in the affairs of the government of Montenegro.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","59607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671730","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>We have received no reports about Russian interference in the affairs of the government of the Czech Republic or Slovakia.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-19T16:50:45.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671730/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671730/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671730/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Russia: Czech Republic and Slovakia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on alleged Russian interference in the affairs of the government of (a) the Czech Republic and (b) Slovakia.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","59606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671731","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>We have received no reports about Russian interference in the affairs of the government of Bulgaria.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-19T16:52:11.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671731/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671731/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671731/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Russia: Bulgaria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on alleged Russian interference in the affairs of the government of Bulgaria; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","59608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671732","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Government is working with Algeria to achieve its goals of sustainable security, stability and prosperity in the country and the wider region.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-16T16:30:14.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671732/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671732/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671732/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Algeria: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the objectives of the Government's diplomatic and political policy on Algeria are for 2017.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","59628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671733","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>The UK's primary objective in Mali remains to support the country in providing long-term stability. To achieve this we are working closely with international partners to support the implementation of the Peace Accord as well as building the capacity of the Malian civilian and military security forces, combating violent extremism and tackling irregular migration. We are also providing humanitarian and development assistance that helps Mali, and the wider Sahel region, become more resilient to climatic and economic shocks, with greater economic opportunities and better social protection.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-16T16:32:06.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671733/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671733/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671733/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Mali: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the objectives of the Government's diplomatic and political policy on Mali are for 2017.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","59629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671734","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>​The Government is committed to supporting Tunisia to realise its ambitions as a stable democracy with a growing economy, and to help the country to maintain its security in light of the threats from terrorism in the region.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-16T16:37:12.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671734/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671734/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671734/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Tunisia: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the objectives of the Government's diplomatic and political policy on Tunisia are for 2017.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","59630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671735","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson) released a statement on 15 January where he outlined the UK’s firm opposition to the death penalty. It is our longstanding position to oppose capital sentences in all circumstances. The Bahraini authorities are fully aware of our position and the Foreign Secretary has raised the issue with the Government of Bahrain.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-19T16:28:49.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671735/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671735/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671735/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Bahrain: Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the government of Bahrain on the death sentences against Abbas al-Samea, Sami Mushaima and Ali al-Singace; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","59618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671736","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>Following the signing of Montenegro's Accession Protocol last May, the UK was the first major NATO Ally to ratify it in November 2016. The Foreign Secretary met with Montenegrin Foreign Minister Darmanovic in the margins of the NATO Foreign Ministers meeting on 7 December 2016 and reiterated the UK's strong support for Montenegro's accession. He also urged other NATO Allies to ensure that their own ratification processes proceeded as swiftly as possible, to ensure that Montenegro can take its place as the 29<sup>th</sup> member of the Alliance in the first half of 2017.</p><p>In addition to political support, the UK has provided practical assistance throughout the accession process. We have for example continued to provide capacity building support in a range of areas, including strategic communications, public diplomacy and senior defence leadership training. We hope shortly to sign a Memorandum of Understanding that will underpin military cooperation between the UK and Montenegro.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-19T16:53:43.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671736/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671736/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671736/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Montenegro: NATO","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to assist Montenegro's application to join NATO.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","59579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671737","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Ascension Island Government will aim to introduce the best biosecurity industry standards for all imported equipment and construction materials utilised in the runway resurfacing project.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-19T16:54:31.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671737/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671737/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671737/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Ascension Island: Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what biosecurity standards will be followed when equipment and construction materials are imported into Ascension Island for resurfacing that island's runway.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","59581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671738","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-16","<p>Guided missile kits are not standard descriptors used on strategic export licence statistics. Information on arms export licences including higher assembly platforms, are published as Official Statistics in the Annual and Quarterly Reports on Strategic Export Controls. These reports contain detailed information on export licences issued, refused or revoked, by destination, including the overall value, type (e.g. Military, Other) and a summary of the items covered by these licences. They are available to view at GOV.UK.</p><p>All export licences are issued in strict accordance with the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-01-16T17:54:54.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671738/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671738/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671738/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-11","Saudi Arabia: Arms Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many export licences for the sale of guided missile kits to Saudi Arabia have been granted in the last five years; and when the last such licence was granted.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","59675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671739","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-16","<p>We continue to urge all parties to the conflict to take all reasonable steps to facilitate rapid and safe humanitarian access. DFID is supporting the UN Verification and Inspection Mechanism, the UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs and the UN Humanitarian Air Service to improve access for vital commercial imports of food and for humanitarian aid.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-16T17:47:55.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671739/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671739/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671739/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-11","Yemen: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to improve access for aid organisations to deliver humanitarian assistance to affected areas in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","59676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671740","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-16","<p>The UK is at the forefront of the humanitarian response to the Syria crisis. We have committed £2.3 billion, of which £436 million supports UN agencies delivering aid inside Syria. We are using all our diplomatic tools to press the Syrian regime and its backers to allow the UN immediate and unhindered access to all those in need across Syria. As part of this, the UK co-sponsored and lobbied hard to secure UN Security Council Resolutions 2165, 2191, 2258 and 2332 which enable the UN and its partners to deliver aid across borders into Syria without the consent of the Syrian regime. Between July 2014 and December 2016, 467 aid convoys had reached people in dire need through these routes.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-16T17:49:03.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671740/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671740/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671740/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-11","Syria: International Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to support the UN's delivery of aid to affected areas of Syria.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","59677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671741","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>​​The UK is currently co-located with EU countries in nine locatons: The Hague, Chisinau, Niamey, Dar Es Salaam, Gaborone, Port of Spain, Pyongyang, Quito and Juba. We define co-location as circumstances in which there is a financial relationship between us and our co-location partner.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-01-19T17:38:11.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671741/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671741/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671741/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Buildings: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, in which locations the UK shares overseas premises with other EU countries.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","59700"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671742","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>Foreign Office Ministers, our Ambassador to Saudi Arabia and officials have frequent meetings with the Saudi Government and officials to discuss a full range of regional and bilateral issues. The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson), visited Saudi Arabia on 11 December.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-16T16:42:29.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671742/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671742/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671742/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Saudi Arabia: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many meetings (a) Ministers and (b) officials of his Department have had with Saudi government officials in the last six months.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","59678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671743","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>My Rt Hon. Friend the then Foreign Secretary (Phillip Hammond) was made aware of reports that UK-made BL-755 cluster munitions were used in Yemen in an update to the Minister on May 23, 2016.</p><p>The current Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson) was aware of the allegations before entering the office. He was briefed by officials during his first month in office.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-19T16:31:14.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671743/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671743/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671743/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when he first became aware of reports that UK-manufactured cluster bombs were used to target civilians in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","59672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671744","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>Foreign and Commonwealth Office Ministers considered the Vienna Convention implications of the alleged behaviour of an Israeli Embassy official. The Israeli Ambassador has made a full apology and we consider the matter closed.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-16T16:23:41.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671744/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671744/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671744/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Israel: Diplomatic Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the compliance of Israel's diplomatic representatives in the UK with their obligation under article 41 of the 1961 Vienna Convention on Diplomatic Relations on not interfering in the internal affairs of another signatory state; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","59543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671745","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>We are concerned by a number of disturbing reports of human rights violations and violence against Rohingya Muslims by security forces in Rakhine State. We have made several representations to the Government of Burma and called for humanitarian access both through our ambassador and also through Ministerial contacts. The Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my noble Friend, the Rt Hon. Baroness Anelay of St Johns, visited Burma from 9-12 November and urged Burmese Government Ministers to ensure the full resumption of humanitarian aid and to set up an independent investigation into allegations of human rights violations. I also raised this in person with the Burmese Minister of Construction, when he visited London on 29 November. We will continue to monitor developments closely and to raise our concerns at every suitable opportunity.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-01-16T17:36:31.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671745/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671745/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671745/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on violence against Rohingya Muslims in Burma.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","59544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671746","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>My ministerial colleagues and I have regular contact with our Irish counterparts to discuss a wide range of issues, including the UK's exit from the EU, Northern Ireland and defence. I met the Irish Europe Minister Dara Murphy on 8 December 2016; the Foreign Secretary has met his counterpart regularly at the Foreign Affairs Council; and the Prime Minister is due to visit Dublin at the end of January.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-16T17:30:49.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671746/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671746/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671746/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Republic of Ireland: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what was discussed during his most recent exchange with his counterpart in Ireland.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","59545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671747","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-18","<p>There are over 120 officials currently employed at the UK’s Permanent Representation to the EU.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-18T16:35:44.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671747/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671747/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671747/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","UK Permanent Representation to the EU: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many people are employed at the UK Permanent Representation to the EU.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","59526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671748","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Secretary of State regularly speaks with international partners, the private sector and others to stress the importance of global efforts to eradicate poverty, including calling for increased funding to a range of development and humanitarian priorities.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-16T16:19:50.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671748/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671748/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671748/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-11","Foreign Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions she has had with her international counterparts on their progress towards spending 0.7 per cent of their gross national income on overseas aid.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","59517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671749","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>​Engagement with South Sudanese leaders across the political spectrum is a critical component of our efforts to call for an end to the violence and support work towards an inclusive and sustainable resolution to the conflict. The UK Special Envoy to Sudan and South Sudan is tasked with this engagement and regularly meets with South Sudanese opposition leaders, including those in the UK.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-19T14:11:22.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671749/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671749/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671749/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","South Sudan: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what plans the Minister for Africa and the Middle East has to meet with South Sudanese opposition leaders in the UK.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","59505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671750","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Noble Friend, the Rt Hon. Baroness Anelay of St Johns, visited Guatemala, El Salvador, Honduras and Mexico from 12 to 16 December. Throughout her visit she held a number of discussions, with both government and civil society representatives, on the issue of attacks and threats to human rights defenders (HRDs). This included:</p><p> </p><ul><li>In Guatemala, meeting key human rights contacts from the executive, legislature, judiciary and civil society, all of whom agreed on the key role played by HRDs and the need to give them protection;</li><li>In El Salvador, meeting NGOs to discuss threats against the International Committee of the Red Cross and the LGBT&amp;I community. Baroness Anelay also met Supreme Court judges to express the UK's support for their work to defend human rights, especially relating to prisons conditions;</li></ul><ul><li>In Honduras, meeting female HRDs, who described difficulties relating to freedom of expression and the criminalisation and stigmatisation of HRDs; and, during an engagement with government representatives including the Minister for Human Rights, stressing the importance of protecting HRDs and improving the human rights environment in the country; and</li></ul><ul><li>In Mexico, urging the Government to prevent and follow up cases of corruption and torture, and underlining the importance of implementing convincing actions following the disappearance of 43 student teachers in Aytozinapa in 2014; and hearing how female journalists had experienced intimidation after reporting on issues such as enforced disappearances, on which the Minister expressed deep concern.</li></ul>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-19T16:48:51.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671750/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671750/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671750/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Central America and Mexico: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions Ministers and officials of his Department had on the issue of attacks and threats to human rights defenders during the recent visit to Central America and Mexico.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","59507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671751","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>The British Government supports all genuine efforts towards sustained peace in Syria. We welcome the efforts of Russia, Turkey and Iran to secure a ceasefire deal. We hope that talks planned to take place in Astana can contribute to a UN-led political process, although we note a series of ceasefire violations, including by regime forces. Only a political settlement can stop the war and bring the peace the Syrian people deserve. We believe that this will ultimately require a transition away from Asad: he cannot unite the country because of the atrocities he has perpetrated against the Syrian people.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-16T16:26:28.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671751/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671751/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671751/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Syria: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 20 December 2016 to Question 57778, on Syria: Armed Conflict, what the Government's policy is on re-establishing dialogue with the Assad Regime as part of multilateral peace talks.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","59564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671752","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office does not maintain such records centrally.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-19T16:25:59.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671752/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671752/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671752/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Diplomatic Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to his oral contribution of 10 January 2017, Official Report, column 148, which embassies have been asked for apologies on account of their officials' remarks.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","59565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671753","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>​We have not made any assessment on this issue, as we do not make representations on behalf of British nationals, including parliamentarians, wishing to travel to Gaza. Parliamentarians should be aware that the Foreign and Commonwealth Office advises against all travel to Gaza. Entry and exit from Gaza is difficult and can, at times, be impossible. Entry is through either Israel, with permission from the Israeli authorities, or Egypt, with permission from the Egyptian authorities (although this border has been closed almost entirely since October 2014).</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-19T14:16:39.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671753/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671753/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671753/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Gaza: Visits Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the level of cooperation of the Israeli government in fact-finding visits to Gaza by UK parliamentarians.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","59566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671754","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Department for International Development’s (DFID) ongoing examination of UK aid to the Occupied Palestinian Territories has been carried out in close collaboration with the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO). The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson), discussed the review with the Secretary of State for International Development, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witham (Ms Patel), on 13 September 2016. On 16 December 2016 , the FCO and DFID issued a joint statement confirming the continuation of UK support to the Palestinian Authority.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-19T14:19:21.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671754/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671754/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671754/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Occupied Territories: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for International Development on the review of funding to the Occupied Palestinian Territories.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","59567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671755","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>​We remain deeply concerned by the situation in Gaza. I raised this with the Israeli Deputy Foreign Minister on 12 December and officials from our Embassy in Tel Aviv also raised the situation with the Israeli authorities on 5 December. Officials from our Embassy in Tel Aviv and our Consulate General in Jerusalem regularly raise the need to make progress towards a durable solution for Gaza, and press for practical steps to advance reconstruction and economic development with both the Israeli Government and the Palestinian Authority.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-19T14:24:46.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671755/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671755/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671755/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Gaza: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the Israeli government on the restriction of building materials entering Gaza.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","59568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671756","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>The EU has not to date asked for compensation for EU funded infrastructure. No decision has been made yet as to whether to claim compensation in the future. The UK is focused on preventing these demolitions from happening in the first place, and supporting those affected. We are working with other EU member states to make clear to Israel the need to provide a reasonable means for Palestinians to gain planning permission in Israeli controlled areas of the West Bank (Area C) and the need to halt all demolitions until a more effective process is in-place.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-19T16:23:44.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671756/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671756/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671756/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","West Bank: Demolition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what his Department's policy is on EU member states seeking compensation from the Israeli government as a result of that country's demolition of EU-funded structures in Area C of the West Bank.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","59551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671757","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>The UK continues to actively engage and work with the US on the current situation in Yemen to find a peaceful solution to the conflict. The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson) last met with Senator Kerry to discuss the situation in Yemen at the Quadrilateral in London on 16 October. I met with Senator Kerry at the Quadrilateral in Riyadh on 18 December.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-19T16:21:11.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671757/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671757/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671757/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","USA: Yemen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he had with the US administration on Yemen during his recent visit to the US in January 2017; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","59531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671758","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson) has no current plans to visit Yemen.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-19T14:14:31.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671758/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671758/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671758/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-11","Yemen: Visits Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when he next plans to visit Yemen.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","59533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671759","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>NHS England is currently in the process of tendering for a veterans mental health service to begin in April 2017. The service will offer consistent support across England for both veterans and serving personnel on a pathway to leave the service and build on the veterans mental health services already in place following the Fighting Fit report by my hon. Friend the Member for South West Wiltshire (Dr Andrew Murrison).</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-16T17:11:25.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671759/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671759/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671759/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","Mental Health Services: Veterans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what additional support services his Department is planning to provide for veterans with mental health problems from April 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Prisk","Hertford and Stortford","Mr Mark Prisk","59557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671760","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Department does not assess services provided by the voluntary sector.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-16T16:15:01.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671760/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671760/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671760/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","Mental Health Services: Veterans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the standard and availability of support for veterans with mental health problems provided by the voluntary sector.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Prisk","Hertford and Stortford","Mr Mark Prisk","59555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671761","Department of Health","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Department takes advice on all aspects of screening from the independent UK National Screening Committee (UK NSC). The UK NSC is currently reviewing its recommendation on antenatal screening for Group B Streptococcus carriage as part of its three yearly review cycle. A public consultation is currently open and will be closing on 25 January. The UK NSC will consider the evidence and consultation responses at its meeting in February 2017.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-19T14:18:56.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671761/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671761/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671761/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","Pregnancy: Streptococcus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if his Department will take steps to make group B streptococcus screening routinely available to all pregnant women.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","59548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671762","Department of Health","false","2017-01-19","<p>Proposals have been published for all 44 Sustainability Transformation Plans (STPs) covering every part of England.</p><p> </p><p>STPs evolved during last year and will continue to do so as each local area discusses the thinking with staff, patients and local people. These conversations are still taking place and STPs will continue to evolve to reflect them.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-19T11:49:48.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671762/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671762/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671762/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","NHS: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress there has been to date on the development of sustainability and transformation plans; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","59549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671763","Department of Health","false","2017-01-19","<p>Sustainability and Transformation Plans (STPs) continue to develop, as each local area discusses their proposals with staff, patients and local people.</p><p> </p><p>As a result, it is not possible to develop an aggregate total for the total level of capital funding requested to deliver the STPs.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-19T11:48:14.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671763/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671763/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671763/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","NHS: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what total level of capital funding is requested in the 44 sustainability and transformation plans for the delivery of those plans.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","59550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671764","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Department has received no such representations from NHS England.</p><p> </p><p>My Rt. Hon. Friend the Secretary of State confirmed on 11 January 2017, Official Report, column 352, that he remained committed to maintaining the four hour accident and emergency (A&amp;E) standard for those attending A&amp;E.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-16T17:29:36.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671764/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671764/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671764/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what representations he has received from NHS England on changing the four-hour accident and emergency waiting target.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","59561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671765","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>The proportion of patients who have attended accident and emergency (A&amp;E) departments because they have been unable to get a timely appointment with their general practitioner (GP) is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to improving access to GP services. By 2020, everyone will be able to access routine GP appointments at evenings and weekends. 17 million patients have already benefitted from extended access to GP appointments at evenings and weekends through the GP Access Fund.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-16T17:13:08.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671765/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671765/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671765/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of patients have attended accident and emergency departments because they have been unable to get a timely appointment with their GP in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","59562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671766","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Department has received advice from external professional advisers on the potential sale of a stake in NHS Professionals Ltd, announced on 17 November 2016. In line with standard commercial procurement practice, the information requested cannot be released as it is commercially sensitive.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-16T16:18:45.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671766/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671766/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671766/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","NHS Professionals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will publish the advice his Department has received on privatising NHS Professionals.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","59563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671767","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>Following a national engagement exercise during 2016 on mental health services for veterans, NHS England commissioned a pathfinder transition, intervention and liaison mental health service for armed forces serving personnel approaching discharge and after discharge.</p><p> </p><p>The service has been launched and is a joint initiative between the National Health Service and the Ministry of Defence and will run until the end of March 2017. The evidence from this service will help to shape the service specification from April 2017.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-16T16:09:54.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671767/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671767/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671767/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","Mental Health Services: Veterans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress has been made in the joint commissioning of services to support former service personnel with mental health problems.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Prisk","Hertford and Stortford","Mr Mark Prisk","59556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671768","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>Capita has made NHS England aware of a number of issues involving the National Dental Performers List process. Immediate action has been taken to put in place plans to recover the services.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-16T16:16:37.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671768/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671768/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671768/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","Capita: Dental Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of Capita's performance in processing dental performer list applications for newly qualified dentists; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Selous","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","59559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671769","Department of Health","false","2017-01-19","<p>NHS England is responsible for the National Dental Performers list and currently does not hold information centrally on how many applications have been received from individuals wishing to join the National Dental Performers list. Information on the length of time to process applications is therefore currently not available.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-19T11:25:07.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671769/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671769/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671769/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","Dental Services: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the average processing time was for a performer number to be provided to a dentist in each of the last 24 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","59508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671770","Department of Health","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Department does not collect information on the number of registered and active general practitioners (GPs) that obtained their initial qualifications in the United Kingdom.</p><p> </p><p>The General Medical Council has provided the following information:</p><p> </p><p>77.6% of registered GPs obtained their initial qualification in the UK, this is 52,615 of 67,771; and</p><p> </p><p>78.6% of registered GPs with a licence to practise obtained their initial qualification in the UK, this is 48,043 of 61,096.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-19T14:24:21.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671770/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671770/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671770/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","General Practitioners: Qualifications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of (a) registered and (b) active GPs obtained their initial qualifications in the UK.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","59509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671771","Department of Health","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Department can confirm following a detailed search of its Business Management Services database, that “The Grace Partnership” are not a registered supplier and consequently there are no records of any spend or contracts being held with this company.</p><p> </p><p>Responses from all of the Department’s Non-Departmental Public Bodies and its agencies, including special health authorities, have confirmed that no contracts are or have been held with The Grace Partnership since 2014.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-19T16:38:17.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671771/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671771/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671771/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","Department of Health: Grace Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many contracts (a) his Department and (b) its non-departmental bodies and agencies have awarded to The Grace Partnership since 2014.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","59501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671772","Department of Health","false","2017-01-19","<p>General practitioners (GPs) are independent contractors who hold contracts with NHS England to provide primary medical services for the National Health Service. Under the terms of their contract, GPs are required to provide certain medical reports or complete certain forms, such as those required to support a claim for incapacity benefit, free of charge to their registered patients.</p><p> </p><p>Outside of contractual requirements, GPs also provide a variety of other services which successive governments have regarded as private matters between the patient and the GP providing these services. In such cases, decisions on whether to charge a fee and the level of the fee charged are at the GP’s discretion. Where GPs intend to charge for services to patients, the British Medical Association (BMA) advises them to forewarn patients, at the earliest opportunity, of the likely level of fees. The BMA also produces guidance on the level of fees that should be charged for various services.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-19T12:04:42.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671772/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671772/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671772/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","Medical Certificates: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make it his policy to end the practice of GPs charging patients for letters to prove sickness in support of debt collection, housing or welfare claims.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","59510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671773","Department of Health","false","2017-01-19","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-19T14:22:50.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671773/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671773/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671773/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","Ambulance Services: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much the NHS has spent on private ambulances in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","59511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671774","Department of Health","false","2017-01-18","<p>The information is not available in the format requested.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-18T12:01:57.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671774/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671774/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671774/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","Diabetes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the estimated cost to the NHS was of accident and emergency admissions for people with diabetes complications in each of the last three years.","true","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","59529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671775","Department of Health","false","2017-01-19","<p>NHS England advises that its south west office funded a Local Enhanced Service contract, which ensured that St Martin’s Surgery had robust governance methods in place. That included logging all notes and maintaining a log book covering receipt/transfer of notes. Final sign-off was made by directors of NHS England south west and the Caldicott Guardian.</p><p> </p><p>When a general practitioner practice closes, NHS England is responsible for ensuring that patients have continued access to NHS primary medical services. They can do this either by allocating patients to another practice in the area or by advertising for another contract holder.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England determines both the services required in the area and the provider best able to deliver them. Under section 13Q of the National Health Service Act 2006, NHS England is required to involve those to whom the services are being or may be provided in the process of deciding how those services are to be delivered.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","59522","2017-01-19T11:53:11.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671775/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671775/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671775/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","General Practitioners: Bristol","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps NHS England has taken to ensure the smooth transition of hard copy records of patients who need to re-register from St Martin's Surgery, Knowle, Bristol, to other practices as a result of that surgery's closure.","false","Biography information for Karin Smyth","Bristol South","Karin Smyth","59521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671776","Department of Health","false","2017-01-19","<p>NHS England advises that its south west office funded a Local Enhanced Service contract, which ensured that St Martin’s Surgery had robust governance methods in place. That included logging all notes and maintaining a log book covering receipt/transfer of notes. Final sign-off was made by directors of NHS England south west and the Caldicott Guardian.</p><p> </p><p>When a general practitioner practice closes, NHS England is responsible for ensuring that patients have continued access to NHS primary medical services. They can do this either by allocating patients to another practice in the area or by advertising for another contract holder.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England determines both the services required in the area and the provider best able to deliver them. Under section 13Q of the National Health Service Act 2006, NHS England is required to involve those to whom the services are being or may be provided in the process of deciding how those services are to be delivered.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","59521","2017-01-19T11:53:11.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671776/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671776/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671776/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","General Practitioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department takes to help patients whose GP surgery closes to re-register elsewhere.","false","Biography information for Karin Smyth","Bristol South","Karin Smyth","59522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671777","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs (Defra) is the lead government department for the response to avian influenza incidents in the United Kingdom. Public Health England (PHE) supports Defra by advising on the potential impacts on human health and coordinating actions to mitigate any impact on human health.</p><p> </p><p>PHE has introduced a number of measures, in relation to avian influenza, which are applicable to the current Avian Influenza A (H5N8) incidents in the UK. This includes: issuing public health guidance for health protection teams and health professionals in supporting the response to poultry outbreaks and wild bird incidents; maintaining laboratory capability to test for suspected avian influenza infections in humans, through the PHE laboratory network and reference laboratory; developing and publishing a risk assessment of the public health implications of avian influenza incidents and outbreaks; and monitoring international trends through epidemic intelligence.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, in response to the poultry outbreaks and wild bird incidents, PHE has worked to identify persons directly exposed in these incidents and provide them with health advice, undertake health surveillance and, where appropriate, ensure they have access to post-exposure prophylaxis with Neuraminidase Inhibitors (otherwise known as antivirals). PHE has also undertaken a risk assessment in conjunction with Defra, and worked to provide information and advice on the public health and human aspects of this incident.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-16T17:19:17.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671777/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671777/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671777/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","Avian Influenza","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department has taken in response to the pathogenic avian influenza H5N8 outbreak in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","59516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671778","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>We will be publishing a report in 2018 on the mental health survey of children and young people that we commissioned in 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The mental health prevalence survey for adults is conducted every seven years. The last adult survey was published on 29 September 2016. This information is available on NHS Digital’s website at:</p><p> </p><p>http://content.digital.nhs.uk/catalogue/PUB21748</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-16T16:56:19.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671778/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671778/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671778/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Five Year Forward View in Mental Health of February 2016, when his Department plans to publish mental health prevalence surveys for (a) children, (b) young people and (c) adults.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","59705"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671779","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>The National Health Service will be receiving £10 billion more per year in real terms by 2020-21 compared to 2014-15. Real terms funding for the NHS in 2018-19 will rise by 0.3%, as illustrated in the following table which sets out the financial settlement allocated to the NHS.</p><p> </p><p>NHS budget for Spending Review period<sup>1</sup></p><table><thead><tr><td><p>Revenue and capital combined</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>2018-19</p></td><td><p>2019-20</p></td><td><p>2020-21</p></td></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><p>Total (£ million)</p></td><td><p>100,500</p></td><td><p>105,975</p></td><td><p>109,337</p></td><td><p>111,824</p></td><td><p>114,929</p></td><td><p>119,035</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Real terms increase on previous year (%)</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>3.7%</p></td><td><p>1.3%</p></td><td><p>0.3%</p></td><td><p>0.7%</p></td><td><p>1.3%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Real terms increase on 2015-16 baseline (£ billion)</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>3.8</p></td><td><p>5.3</p></td><td><p>5.8</p></td><td><p>6.7</p></td><td><p>8.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Real terms increase on 2014-15 baseline (£ billion)</p></td><td><p>2.0</p></td><td><p>6.0</p></td><td><p>7.0</p></td><td><p>8.0</p></td><td><p>9.0</p></td><td><p>10.0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><sup>1</sup>These figures differ from the NHS Total Departmental Expenditure Limit figures announced at Spending Review due to a number of technical adjustments, including transfers of functions. The main transfer of function is the move of public health services for 0-5 year olds from NHS England to local government. There are a small number of other transfers including the move of the Leadership Academy to Health Education England. To ensure comparability of numbers, in this table £500 million has been removed from the 2015-16 baseline, representing 6 months of funding for 0-5 public health services between 1 April and 30 September 2015 and these other planned transfers.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-16T17:35:32.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671779/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671779/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671779/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the evidence of Sir Simon Stevens to the Public Accounts Committee on 11 January 2017, whether real terms funding for the NHS will fall in 2018-19.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","59706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671780","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Department’s allocation to NHS England in 2015-16 equates to £1,835 spend per capita in 2015-16.</p><p>It is not possible to provide a corresponding figure for 2010-11 as NHS England only came into existence in 2013-14.</p><p>The Department’s overall spend per capita in 2010-11 was £1,908 and £2,140 in 2015-16.</p><p>Departmental overall spend per capita has grown by 12.2% between 2010-11 and 2015-16.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-16T17:27:36.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671780/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671780/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671780/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","NHS: Per Capita Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much funding his Department (a) allocates to the NHS per capita at present and (b) allocated per capita in 2010; and what percentage change in funding per capita there has been between 2010 and 2016.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","59703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671781","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>Since February 2016, Time to Change has registered 1,871 champions. These champions are adults with lived experience of mental health, who lead the Time to Change anti-stigma movement and provide peer support.</p><p> </p><p>In order to contribute to the relevant recommendation in the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health to establish mental health champions in each community, since April 2016 they have also had 84 young champions in place as part of their children and young people’s programme.</p><p> </p><p>In total, Time to Change now have 8,411 champions to date.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-16T17:22:32.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671781/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671781/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671781/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many Mental Health Champions his Department has established since the publication of the Five Year Forward View in Mental Health in February 2016.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","59704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671782","Department of Health","false","2017-01-19","<p>The £200 million fund NHS England announced in December 2016 will be available to Cancer Alliances over the next two years to specifically support the areas the Cancer Taskforce strategy estimated would need additional investment including implementing the Recovery Package and rolling out stratified follow up pathways.</p><p> </p><p>Initial bids for funding are due on 18 January 2017. Clear guidance has been published and a regional and national panel will assess all bids received. The funding will be signed off by the NHS England Investment Committee.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-19T11:56:42.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671782/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671782/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671782/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","Cancer: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to NHS England's announcement on 6 December 2016 of an additional £200 million to improve local cancer services, what plans he has to ensure that that money will be used to roll out the Recovery Package and stratified pathways of follow-up care as costed in the Independent Cancer Taskforce report.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","59671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671783","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>The information requested is in the table below.</p><p> </p><p>Number of beds<sup>1</sup> and physicians<sup>2</sup> per 1,000 people in England in 2010 and present<sup>3</sup> and the global ranking of the United Kingdom<sup>4</sup> for those measures<sup>5</sup></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Q2 2010/11</p></td><td><p>Q2 2016/17</p></td><td><p>September 2010</p></td><td><p>September 2015</p></td><td><p>UK global ranking (OECD countries) 2010</p></td><td><p>UK global ranking (OECD countries) 2014</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Beds</p></td><td><p>2.74</p></td><td><p>2.34</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>29/35</p></td><td><p>27/35</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Physicians</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2.70</p></td><td><p>2.73</p></td><td><p>N/A<sup>6</sup></p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source:</em> Beds availability and occupancy, NHS England. Office for National Statistics population mid-year estimates and projections and 2011 census. Workforce statistics, NHS Digital. OECD global ranking data.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><em>Notes:</em></p><ol><li>Number of available consultant-led beds open overnight.</li><li>All doctors in General Practice and Hospital and Community Health Services</li><li>The most current available data has been used.</li><li>Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) data for hospital beds in 2010 and 2014 as the latest complete dataset.</li><li>OECD data on number of beds per capita should only be used to make international comparisons with caution, because of inconsistencies in the basis and coverage of the data. The OECD report may not be comparing like with like. For example, some European countries may have included nursing home beds or private sector beds in their figures, which would not be included in the UK figures. In addition, differences between European health systems make comparisons very difficult. Some countries still have large long-stay hospitals for people with mental health problems and older people, whilst England has very few such facilities. The National Health Service also has a strong tradition of primary care and is committed to providing proactive support particularly to frail older people and those with long term conditions in the community.</li><li>UK global ranking data is not held centrally for physicians.</li></ol>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-16T17:38:16.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671783/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671783/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671783/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many (a) hospital beds and (b) physicians per 1,000 people there (i) are at present and (ii) were in 2010; and what the UK's global ranking for those measures (A) is at present and (B) was in 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","59702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671785","Department of Health","false","2017-01-19","<p>Selective Internal Radiation Therapy is not currently routinely funded by the NHS England. However, it is available via Individual Funding Requests.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has decided not to routinely fund SIRT because there is insufficient evidence of clinical effectiveness. Clinical commissioning policies are developed and determined in line with a published process that has been subject to consultation and developed with the input of public and patient representatives. The process includes a systematic review of the available clinical evidence and stakeholder engagement (including a period of formal public engagement on the draft policy proposition).</p><p> </p><p>The procedure is available here:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/wp-content/uploads/sites/12/2016/06/prioritisation-method-cons-response.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/wp-content/uploads/sites/12/2016/06/prioritisation-method-cons-response.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The evidence review, conducted at the time of the initial publication of NHS England’s clinical commissioning policy which set this position out was omitted from publication in error. However, the evidence is now available on NHS England’s website alongside the policy itself.</p><p> </p><p>In order to gather new evidence, NHS England is providing short-term funding to a number of patients as part of the Commissioning through Evaluation (CtE) programme. This is a formal evaluation programme within a small number of participating centres.</p><p> </p><p>The recruitment phase of this scheme will be coming to an end shortly, after 3.5 years, enabling the analysis phase to begin. It is expected that over 500 patients will have been recruited to the programme by the end March 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The National Institute for Health and Clinical Excellence will act as an independent evaluator and therefore will lead on the production of the final report for the scheme. To ensure that they have a chance to input views, NHS England has agreed that both manufacturers known to have a direct business interest in SIRT will be given an opportunity to comment on this draft report. However, given potential conflicts of interest the CtE Steering Group which includes representation from both patients and national clinical experts will lead in supporting the drafting of the report.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","59648 ; 59649 ; 59650","2017-01-19T12:08:20.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671785/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671785/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671785/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","Radiotherapy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, for what reason the Selective Internal Radiation Therapy (SIRT) evidence summary is not appended to the SIRT interim clinical commissioning policy statement on the NHS England website; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","59647"
