"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671907","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>All UK organisations are responsible for protecting their information and preventing hostile actors from acquiring that data. Political parties can, and should, take steps to ensure their systems are suitably protected. The National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC) offers UK organisations access to the best cyber security advice and support. This advice, if correctly implemented, goes a long way to reducing the prospect of compromise or data loss.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-01-24T16:17:08.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671907/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671907/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671907/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-11","Political Parties: Cybercrime","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have advised UK political parties of the potential threat of cyber-attacks of the kind allegedly made recently by foreign security services in countries such as the USA, Sweden and Germany.","false","Biography information for Lord Rennard",,"Lord Rennard","HL4576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671908","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-18","<p>The Government have not made an assessment of the potential influence of fake news on voting in the UK. Department for Culture, Media and Sport are currently considering the implications of the dissemination of fake news on social media sites more broadly.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-01-18T13:47:20.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671908/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671908/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671908/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-11","Internet: Disinformation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the potential influence of fake news disseminated via the internet on voting in the UK; and whether they are taking steps to limit that influence.","false","Biography information for Lord Rennard",,"Lord Rennard","HL4577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671909","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-26","<p>The total advertising spend for April to December 2016 was £77.3m excluding VAT. This does not include agency fees and production costs. The budget for January to end March 2017 is under discussion.</p><p>HMRC is currently running an advertising campaign to encourage take-up of Married Couple’s Tax Allowance. The total projected media spend for 2016-17, excluding production costs and fees, is £688,577 excluding VAT.</p><p>The Government do not categorise activity by ‘public information’ and ‘non-public information’.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-01-26T14:22:57.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671909/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671909/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671909/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-11","Cabinet Office: Advertising","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the cost of their advertising budget in the current financial year; how much of that budget is for public information; and what, in particular, is the cost of promoting the married couples’ tax allowance.","false","Biography information for Lord Rennard",,"Lord Rennard","HL4578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671910","The Senior Deputy Speaker","false","2017-01-17","<p>It is expected that the arms of the Chair of State in the House of Lords Robing Room will be reupholstered in the next financial year. The back of the seat will be left intact but its condition will continue to be monitored in case further restoration work is required.</p>",,"Lord McFall of Alcluith",,"2017-01-17T12:59:08.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671910/answer","Biography information for Lord McFall of Alcluith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671910/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671910/answer",,,,,"204",,"Senior Deputy Speaker (HoL)","2017-01-11","Chair of State","2","House of Lords","To ask the Senior Deputy Speaker when the Chair of State in the House of Lords Robing Room will be reupholstered.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL4579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671911","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-23","<p>The UK is supporting the UN and its partners to provide blankets, sleeping bags and other emergency assistance to those displaced by the fighting in Wadi Barada. The UN are being prevented from delivering support into Wadi Barada itself by the Regime and its allied militia. The UN has called on all sides to allow safe and unimpeded humanitarian access. Once safe access is secured, our humanitarian partners’ priorities will be to respond to food and water shortages and serious medical cases.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-01-23T17:16:56.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671911/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671911/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671911/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-11","Syria: Humanitarian Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what humanitarian aid is being sent to the Syrian villages of Wadi Barada following the bombing and attacks by heavy artillery, rocket bombardment and gun and sniper fire in early January.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL4580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671912","Home Office","false","2017-01-17","<p>On 21 July 2016, the Government announced its decision to close the Cedars pre-departure accommodation facility. The future use of the site will be a matter for the landlord.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-17T17:09:14.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671912/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671912/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671912/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-11","Cedars Pre-departure Accommodation Facility","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they intend to use the Cedars deportation centre following its closure.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL4581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671913","Department for Education","false","2017-01-20","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that every looked after child receives the high quality care they need in a placement that is suitable for them. We are working with partners to increase the number of suitable placements for unaccompanied asylum seeking children.</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities may apply for funding through the £140m Controlling Migration Fund to support capacity building including the recruitment, approval and training of foster carers. In addition, we are funding the Refugee Council and ECPAT to deliver training for foster carers and support workers across the country who are not experienced in working with unaccompanied asylum seeking or refugee children. We have also committed to evaluate the need for any additional training required by foster carers looking after unaccompanied children as part of our wider safeguarding strategy for unaccompanied asylum seeking and refugee children, which will be published by 1 May 2017.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-01-20T13:27:43.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671913/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671913/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671913/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-11","Asylum: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they are ensuring that there are sufficient numbers of foster parents to accept unaccompanied young asylum seekers.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL4582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671914","Home Office","false","2017-01-17","<p>The Home Office publishes quarterly figures on the number of asylum seekers housed in dispersed accommodation by country of nationality and UK region in the Immigration Statistics release. These figures do not include those asylum seekers who do not receive Home Office support and who either accommodate themselves or stay with family and friends.</p><p>In addition for those refugees resettled in the UK under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme the Home Office publishes the number of people resettled, broken down by local authority, on a quarterly basis</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-17T17:09:45.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671914/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671914/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671914/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-11","Asylum: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which local authorities in England and Wales have accepted Syrian asylum seekers; and how many have been accommodated in each area.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL4583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671915","Home Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>Home Office funding is available for unaccompanied asylum seeking children who are being looked after by local authorities because there is not a suitable adult to care for them.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-24T15:06:41.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671915/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671915/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671915/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-11","Asylum: Children in Care","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Home Office funding to local authorities in respect of the costs of supporting unaccompanied asylum-seeking children (UASCs) is available irrespective of whether a UASC is housed in local authority or private accommodation.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL4584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671916","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-25","<p>The Government has been clear that while we remain an EU Member State, we will abide by our obligations and exercise our rights. We will continue to play our full role in the EU up until the very moment we leave. Once we are outside of the EU we will no longer elect members of the European Parliament.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2017-01-25T15:35:34.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671916/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671916/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671916/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-11","European Parliamentary Elections Act 2002","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government at what stage of the process of leaving the EU the European Parliamentary Elections Act 2002 will be repealed.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL4585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671917","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-24","<p>Social enterprises are businesses with primarily social/environmental objectives, whose surpluses are principally reinvested for that purpose in the business or community rather than mainly being paid to shareholders or owners. We are currently refreshing our own government estimates of the nature and size of the social enterprise market in the UK, and we will publish our research early in 2017.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2017-01-24T12:31:01.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671917/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671917/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671917/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-11","Social Enterprises","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Lord Ashton of Hyde on 10 January (HL Deb, col 1856), what is their definition of a social enterprise.","false","Biography information for Lord Tebbit",,"Lord Tebbit","HL4586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671918","Department for Education","false","2017-01-23","<p>The Government supports children from homes where English is not spoken in a number of ways. At present, it is up to local authorities to decide whether to include English as an Additional Language (EAL) as a factor in the local formulae for funding schools. 136 used an EAL factor in the current year, with per pupil values ranging from below £100 to over £3000. However, in our proposals for the National Funding Formula, currently under consultation, we have proposed that all children with EAL will attract an additional £515 (primary) or £1385 (secondary) to their school, for the first 3 years after they enter the state system, wherever they are in the country. This is proposed to come in from 2018-19.</p><p>Where children are educating at home instead of in school, parents who educate a child at home must provide a full-time education suitable to the child’s age, ability and aptitudes, and it is likely that such an education would need to include lessons in English to meet that requirement.</p><p>The Government also supports training for adults in English for Speakers of Other Language (ESOL): to enable unemployed people on benefits to get the skills they need to get into and stay in work; to support the integration of long-standing migrant communities and particularly those individuals most at risk of isolation from services and wider society; and to support refugees, especially Syrians, to resettle in the UK. DfE funds ESOL training through the Adult Education Budget, which is allocated to providers annually by the Skills Funding Agency. In 2015-16 just under £100m was devoted to ESOL provision.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-01-23T15:34:15.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671918/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671918/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671918/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-11","Pupils: English Language","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Lord Nash on 11 January about the risk to children in unrecognised school settings or receiving home education, what specific measures are taken to help children who come from households where English is not spoken.","false","Biography information for Baroness Afshar",,"Baroness Afshar","HL4587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671919","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-24","<p>The Solent to Midlands Route Strategy will identify locations, including the A34, with specific performance pressures and opportunities for improvement, and will inform HM Government’s future decisions in the second Road Investment Strategy, covering investment in the strategic road network beyond 2020.</p><p> </p><p>Alongside this, Government supports greater use of rail for freight transport and is providing £235 million of funding during Control Period 5 (2014 – 2019) to the Strategic Freight Network Fund. This funding is being utilised to increase the capacity and capability of our rail network to support rail freight.</p><p> </p><p>Specifically in the A34 area, considerable investment is being made within Control Period 5 on the routes out of Southampton to allow longer and heavier freight trains to run. These enhancements provide the capability and capacity to transport more freight by rail, helping to take lorries off our roads.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-01-24T12:27:58.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671919/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671919/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671919/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-11","A34","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 5 January (HL4289), what plans they have for increasing the volume of heavy freight transported by rail, to provide relief to the A34 prior to the implementation of the updated route strategy.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL4588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671920","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-23","<p>We expect to appoint the Commissioner in 2017 and we continue to make progress on implementation. Our public consultation on the policy for regulations underpinning the Commissioner’s complaints handling function closed in December and we are preparing the Government Response.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-01-23T12:10:04.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671920/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671920/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671920/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-11","Small Business Commissioner","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Neville-Rolfe on 11 May 2016 (HL8016), what further progress has been made towards appointing the proposed Small Business Commissioner to help small businesses resolve payment disputes with large businesses.","false","Biography information for Baroness Golding",,"Baroness Golding","HL4589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671921","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-18","<p>Under existing (international) firearm and safety regulations, airlines may carry unloaded guns and a limited amount of ammunition in hold baggage where persons are holding these lawfully. In the UK, there are strict controls on how such items are notified to the air carrier, screened and placed in an aircraft hold leaving the UK and on collecting such items on entry to the UK. Passengers are prohibited from carrying firearms and ammunition in the cabin of an aircraft; and passengers and their cabin baggage are screened for such items prior to departure.</p><p> </p><p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office US travel advice was updated on 7 January in light of the Fort Lauderdale incident to advise travellers to follow local procedures.</p><p> </p><p>We keep our aviation security measures under constant review.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-01-18T13:45:58.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671921/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671921/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671921/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-11","Aviation: Firearms","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what measures they are taking to ensure that airline passengers arriving at or departing from UK airports are not allowed to carry guns or ammunition either in the passenger cabin or in checked hold baggage; and whether they will provide warnings to airline passengers travelling to or from those states in the US where the carrying of guns and ammunition in passenger planes is now permitted.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Chesterton",,"Lord Hunt of Chesterton","HL4590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671922","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>First, I would like to make clear my admiration for the dedication, professionalism and courage shown by soldiers and police officers in Northern Ireland throughout the Troubles. As we made clear in our 2015 Northern Ireland manifesto, this Government will never forget the debt of gratitude we owe them and will never accept any form of equivalence between those who upheld democracy and the rule of law, and those who engaged in terrorism or other forms of paramilitary activity.</p><p> </p><p>This Government understands the concept of parity of esteem, as set out in the 1998 Belfast Agreement, as placing a general obligation on the UK Government to govern in the interests of the whole community and to treat people of different traditions fairly and with equal respect. In the Agreement it is clearly expressed and defined in relation to people living in Northern Ireland. As a general obligation there is no definition of particular circumstances in which it does or does not apply.</p><p> </p><p>The vast majority of the more than 250,000 men and women who served in the Royal Ulster Constabulary and the Armed Forces in Northern Ireland during the Troubles carried out their duties with exemplary professionalism. However, everyone is equal under the law and, where there is evidence of wrongdoing, this should be investigated.</p><p> </p><p>The current mechanisms for investigating the past do not reflect that 90 per cent of deaths in the Troubles were caused by terrorists and are disproportionately focussed on the actions of soldiers and police. That is why this Government supports the full and faithful implementation of the Stormont House Agreement to bring a new, balanced, proportionate and fair approach to dealing with Northern Ireland’s past.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Dunlop",,"2017-01-19T11:43:54.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671922/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671922/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671922/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-01-11","Belfast Agreement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the concept of parity of esteem as outlined in the Belfast Agreement 1998 applies to those members of the security forces who live in Great Britain and are currently facing investigation of incidents that took place in the civil unrest in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL4591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671923","Department of Health","false","2017-01-25","<p>Social care continues to be a key priority for this Government. The Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government has announced that local authorities will have access to £900 million of additional funding for social care over the next two years, including £240 million through the Adult Social Care Support Grant, funded by reforms to the New Homes Bonus, and additional flexibility for local authorities to raise money through the social care precept.</p><p> </p><p>From April 2017, additional social care funds will be made available to local government through the Better Care Fund, rising to £1.5 billion by 2019/20, with funding going direct to councils to ensure health and social care services work together to support older and vulnerable people.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises that there needs to be reform in the medium and long term to encourage high standards across the whole country. We will put social care on a sustainable footing for the future, giving people the comfort of knowing that they will be cared for in their old age.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-01-25T16:00:24.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671923/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671923/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671923/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","Social Services: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration they are giving to identifying new sources of income to meet increasing care costs, especially in the light of the projected growth in the number of people over the age of 75 within the next five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL4592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671924","Department of Health","false","2017-01-25","<p>The Department continues to work with the Care Quality Commission to monitor care home capacity and although there is inevitable churn, we have not seen a significant decline in care home beds.</p><p> </p><p>The Government understands concerns about the pressures in the market. Although local government finances remain tight, Government has provided local authorities access to up to £7.6 billion of new support for social care by 2019/20, so they can increase social care spending in real terms by the end of the Parliament.</p><p> </p><p>The Care Act (2014) placed duties on local authorities making them responsible for ensuring there is an effective pool of quality providers of social care in their area with capacity to meet the needs of their local population. The Department is supporting local authorities to influence their local market through improved market facilitation and commissioning to ensure that local markets are effective.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has worked with Association of Directors of Adult Social Services<strong>,</strong> Local Government Association, the care sector and other partners to produce a wide range of guidance and support about market shaping and commissioning. We have brought this together in an online hub called Adult Social Care Market Shaping which is an online only resource widely available to people and organisations including local authorities, service users, and care providers.</p><p> </p><p>The Department continues to monitor capacity and effectiveness of the market.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-01-25T15:59:40.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671924/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671924/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671924/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-11","Care Homes: Closures","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the number of private care homes likely to close during 2017 due to local authorities not being able to pay fees; and what alternative provision will be made to accommodate displaced elderly and infirm residents in order to avoid increased demands for hospital bed spaces.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL4593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671925","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-24","<p>The Government's view is that NATO remains the cornerstone of European Defence. Rather than duplicating command structures, the priority for European Union (EU) member states should be to meet the two per cent commitment and to support better cooperation between NATO and the EU. In line with this, Conclusions at the 14 November 2016 EU Foreign Affairs Council (Defence), invited the High Representative/Vice President (HR/VP) to present proposals by spring 2017 for a Member State driven Coordinated Annual Review to aid better capability development and to improve synergies in defence spending. These Conclusions highlighted our key principles that Defence remains a Member State competence and the need for coherence with NATO. We will review the HR/VP's proposals in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-01-24T15:38:15.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671925/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671925/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671925/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-11","EU Defence Policy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what role the UK will play in the implementation of the decision made on 14 November 2016 by EU foreign and defence ministers to seek alignment of national defence planning.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell of Pittenweem",,"Lord Campbell of Pittenweem","HL4594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671926","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-17","<p>The Harpoon system currently carried by the Royal Navy will reach its out of service date in 2018.</p><p>As part of a process of continuously reviewing the capabilities required to deliver their tasking, the Royal Navy is working alongside other areas of the Ministry of Defence to consider options for a Harpoon replacement.</p><p>I am withholding further detail as its disclosure would, or would be likely to, prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-01-17T16:24:06.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671926/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671926/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671926/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-11","Antiship Missiles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what are the reasons for the early withdrawal from service of the Harpoon anti-ship missile from Royal Navy Type 23 Frigates and Type 45 Destroyers; what alternative is available; and when that alternative will be available.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell of Pittenweem",,"Lord Campbell of Pittenweem","HL4595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673732","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-17","<p>It is equally important for the future finances of both women and men that we remain committed to tackling the deficit and strengthening the economy.</p><p> </p><p>Recent government decisions have also been of benefit to women. Around two thirds of those benefitting from the National Living Wage are estimated to be women. And of the 680,000 people who will be lifted out of income tax by 2017/18 as a result of increases in the personal tax allowance, over 60% will be women.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-01-17T14:51:17.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673732/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673732/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673732/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-11","Fiscal Policy: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to ensure that women are not disproportionately affected by the Government's fiscal policies.","false","Biography information for Mr Gavin Shuker","Luton South","Mr Gavin Shuker","908218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673733","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-17","<p>Property valuations for business rates are carried out independently by the Valuation Office Agency and are determined by a number of factors, of which the value of solar panels is just one.</p><p> </p><p>From April 2017, nearly three quarters of all businesses will see no change or a fall in their rates bill, with 600,000 set to pay no business rates at all.</p><p> </p><p>A £3.6bn transitional relief scheme will support the minority of businesses who do face an increase in bills.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-01-17T14:40:56.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673733/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673733/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673733/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-11","Solar Power","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of changes to the rateable value of solar panels on business rates for SMEs and community organisations using that technology.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","908224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673734","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-17","<p>We recognise the need to increase public spending on infrastructure. That’s why, at Autumn Statement 2016, the Chancellor committed additional capital to fund new high-value economic infrastructure through the National Productivity Investment Fund. Coupled with the commitments made at Spending Review 2015, this means annual central government investment in economic infrastructure will now rise by almost 60% between 2016/17 and 2020/21, from £14bn to £22bn.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-01-17T16:41:49.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673734/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673734/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673734/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-11","Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what fiscal steps he is taking to support the development of long-term infrastructure.","false","Biography information for James Berry","Kingston and Surbiton","James Berry","908222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673735","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-17","<p>The investments the government announced at the 2016 Autumn Statement will support a country that works for everyone, no matter where they live. We want to drive up the productivity and growth of every region by investing in their infrastructure, developing the skills of their people and supporting their companies.</p><p>At the 2016 Autumn Statement, the government also announced that Local Enterprise Partnerships in London and The South East will also benefit from £492 million of Local Growth Fund money backing local projects, growth and jobs.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-01-17T16:40:43.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673735/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673735/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673735/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-11","Economic Growth: South East","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to support economic growth in (a) Medway and (b) the South East.","false","Biography information for Rehman Chishti","Gillingham and Rainham","Rehman Chishti","908215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673736","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-17","<p>The Official Development Assistance rules, governed by the OECD Development Assistance Committee, state that spending by all departments on eligible activities can be counted towards UK Official Development Assistance. Therefore, we will count expenditure in 2016 from the following Departments:</p><p> </p><p>The Department for International Development, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, HM Treasury, the Department of Health, the Home Office, the Department for the Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, the Department for Education, The Department of Work and Pensions, the Department for Transport, The Department for Culture, Media and Sport, the Ministry of Defence, HM Revenue and Customs and the Office of National Statistics. The Scottish Government and Welsh Government also undertake activity for which expenditure is counted as UK Official Development Assistance.</p><p> </p><p>Provisional spending on ODA for 2016 will be published in Statistics on International Development in Spring 2017.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-01-17T16:38:06.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673736/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673736/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673736/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-11","Development Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, which government departments' budgets included expenditure counted towards UK Official Development Assistance in 2016.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","908220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673737","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-17","<p>Recent business surveys show that momentum in the economy has continued. The PMI surveys show a broad-based pickup in activity in late 2016, with output growth reaching a 17-month high in December. This is also reflected in the employment level which currently stands at a historically high level of 31.8m, and has increased by 342,000 over the past year.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-01-17T14:48:50.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673737/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673737/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673737/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-11","Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of recent trends in the Purchasing Managers' Index as an indication of future trends in the level of employment.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Quin","Horsham","Jeremy Quin","908216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673738","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-17","<p>Wage growth has now outstripped inflation for 25 consecutive months, the longest period of real wage growth since before the recession. In their November Economic and Fiscal Outlook, the Office for Budget Responsibility forecast wage growth of 2.2% for 2016, and that this would rise to 2.4% in 2017, 2.8% in 2018 and above 3% per annum from 2019 onwards.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-01-17T16:39:32.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673738/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673738/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673738/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-11","Average Earnings","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on wage growth of recent trends in the Office for Budget Responsibility's economic forecasts.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","908221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673739","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-17","<p>The employment level currently stands at a historically high level of 31.8m, and has increased by 342,000 over the past year. This increase has been driven by full-time workers and by high and medium skill occupations, showing the recovery has been producing high quality employment helping to boost productivity and raise living standards across the country.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-01-17T14:42:57.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673739/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673739/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673739/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-11","Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of recent trends in the level of employment.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","908217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673740","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-17","<p>Ultra Low Emission Vehicles (ULEVs) benefit from lower first-year VED rates and lower Company Car Tax rates.</p><p> </p><p>Companies are able to access 100% first-year capital allowances when they install electric chargepoints, and employees will continue to have access to salary sacrifice schemes in order to purchase ULEVs.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is providing approximately £975 million between 2015 and 2020 to support uptake and ULEV manufacturing in the UK.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-01-17T14:39:28.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673740/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673740/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673740/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-11","Motor Vehicles: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what fiscal steps he is taking to support the further take-up of ultra low-emission vehicles.","false","Biography information for Andrew Selous","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","908219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670675","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-17","<p>Remuneration for all grades below Senior Civil Service, including that of Higher Executive Officer, is delegated to each individual department.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-01-17T09:03:36.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670675/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670675/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670675/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-10","Government Departments: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the (a) entry level and (b) top level annual salary for the grade of Higher Executive Officer is in each government department; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","59299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670676","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Cabinet Office does not hold this information centrally. The Cabinet Office complies with the Civil Service Recruitment Principles and the Civil Service Management Code with regard to recruitment practice and the rules around political activities for civil servants.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-01-13T14:22:03.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670676/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670676/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670676/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-10","Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many current civil servants, excluding special advisers, were formerly employed by (a) the Conservative Research Department, (b) Conservative Central Office, (c) Members of Parliament using Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority-provided funds and (d) Members of Parliament using private funds.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","59417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670677","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Emerging Technology and Innovation Analysis Cell (ETIAC) launched as part of the Defence Innovation Initiative by the Secretary of State for Defence had not been established when evidence was drawn for the National Cyber Security Strategy, so it did not make a direct contribution. However, officials from the Ministry of Defence and Home Office (who currently staff ETIAC) did contribute to its conclusions on technology and innovation, as did a range of other stakeholders across Government, industry and academia.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-01-13T11:26:25.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670677/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670677/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670677/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-10","Electronic Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what contribution the Emerging Technology and Innovation Analysis Cell made to the National Cyber Security Strategy 2016-21.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","59402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670678","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Emerging Technology and Innovation Analysis Cell has been renamed the Innovation and Research InSight Unit (IRIS). IRIS was established in summer 2016 and was launched as part of the Defence Innovation Initiative by the Secretary of State for Defence in September 2016. IRIS is based in the Ministry of Defence (MOD) and consists of three full-time MOD employees who will be joined by staff from the Home Office. Formal funding is due to commence in Financial Year 2017-18.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-01-13T14:07:28.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670678/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670678/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670678/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-10","Ministry of Defence: Innovation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when the Emerging Technology and Innovation Analysis Cell was established; what the annual budget is of that Cell; where that Cell is based; and how many staff that Cell employs.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","59499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670679","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Government believes it is appropriate for greater flexibility to be extended to Member States in respect of the ability to apply reduced and zero rates of VAT.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-01-13T11:47:45.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670679/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670679/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670679/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-10","Publications: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he will support the European Commission Proposal for a Council directive amending Directive 2006/112/EC, to enable platform-neutral application of the zero rate of VAT to books, newspapers, magazines and periodical publications in both print and digital forms.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","59475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670680","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-13","<p>HM Treasury has not made any estimate of the daily cost to the UK economy of a strike on the London Underground.</p><p> </p><p>Estimates have been calculated by various business groups but these estimates vary significantly and their accuracy has not been verified.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-01-13T11:51:42.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670680/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670680/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670680/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-10","London Underground: Industrial Disputes","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the daily cost to the UK economy of a strike on the London Underground.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","59401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670681","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-13","<p>HM Revenue and Customs has based the locations of its regional centres on a number of key principles that will enable it to deliver a better and more modern service at lower cost to the taxpayer. They include the quality of local transport links, the local labour market and future workforce supply and retention of staff and skills it needs to continue its transformation.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-01-13T11:48:56.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670681/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670681/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670681/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-10","Revenue and Customs: Leeds","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish the evidential basis for the decision to establish the regional centre for HM Revenue and Customs in Leeds.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","59404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670682","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-18","<p>The government has not made any decisions on the N8 proposal to create a network of Urban Transformation Centres. The government will continue to work with the N8 universities to explore their proposals.</p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy",,"2017-01-18T17:26:22.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670682/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670682/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670682/answer","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670682/answer/previousversion/29876","Biography information for Andrew Percy","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-10","Regional Planning and Development: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many urban transformation centres are planned under the Northern Powerhouse Plan; what the remit of such centres will be; when each such centre will be operational; and how much has been spent and committed on the establishment of such centres to date.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","59418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670683","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-13","<p>The government has not made any decisions on the N8 proposal to create a network of Urban Transformation Centres. The government will continue to work with the N8 universities to explore their proposals.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","59420","2017-01-13T11:06:29.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670683/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670683/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670683/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-10","Regional Planning and Development: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, by what competitive bidding process N8 was established as the delivery partner for the creation of urban transformation centres under the Northern Powerhouse Plan.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","59419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670684","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-16","<p>The apprenticeship levy will apply across the UK and will be collected from employers on a UK wide basis. The expected yield for the apprenticeship levy is published in table C.5: ‘Current Receipts’, in the Autumn Statement 2016 document available here: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/571559/autumn_statement_2016_web.pdf</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-01-16T16:20:44.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670684/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670684/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670684/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-10","Apprentices: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the revenue to be raised from the Apprenticeship Levy from business in Scotland in (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19 and (c) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","59491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670685","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-13","<p>The government has not made any decisions on the N8 proposal to create a network of Urban Transformation Centres. The government will continue to work with the N8 universities to explore their proposals.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","59419","2017-01-13T11:06:29.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670685/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670685/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670685/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-10","Small Businesses: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much has been committed to the North East's fund for small and medium-sized enterprises under the Northern Powerhouse Plan; and from which Government programme or agency such funds have been provided.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","59420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670686","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-18","<p>HM Revenue and Customs does not forecast revenues for Stamp Duty specifically but this forms part of the forecast for Stamp Taxes on Shares, which is an aggregate of Stamp Duty and Stamp Duty Reserve Tax receipts. Forecasts for Stamp Taxes on Shares, along with forecasts for Stamp Duty Land Tax (SDLT) revenue are produced by the Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR) in Table 4.6 of the Economic and Fiscal Outlook (EFO) publication found here: <a href="http://cdn.budgetresponsibility.org.uk/Nov2016EFO.pdf" target="_blank">http://cdn.budgetresponsibility.org.uk/Nov2016EFO.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The latest forecasts were published in November 2016.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-01-18T14:07:52.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670686/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670686/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670686/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-10","Stamp Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the total revenue from stamp duty in the 2017-18 financial year.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","59363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670687","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-18","<p>A zero rate of VAT already applies to many foods, including for example fresh fruit and vegetables. The 20 per cent VAT rate applies to foods such as ice cream, confectionary and potato crisps.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-01-18T13:54:46.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670687/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670687/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670687/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-10","Food: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department has assessed the potential merits of reducing VAT on low-fat percentage food products from 20 to five per cent; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","59266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670688","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-16","<p>As set out in the published prospectus, we have been clear that the new Controlling Migration Fund is about supporting established resident communities coming under pressure from migration, and reflecting locally identified priorities. It also specifically supports action to tackle issues associated with illegal migration, by better enabling local authorities to inform immigration enforcement priorities.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-16T17:03:31.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670688/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670688/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670688/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670688/answer/previousversion/29828","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-10","Public Sector: Immigrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the differences are between the purpose and use of the Migration Impact Fund and the Controlling Migration Fund; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","59253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670689","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-13","<p>From 6 April 2015, the permitted development rights for the change of use or demolition are removed for those pubs the community has demonstrated that it values the most by having nominated them as an Asset of Community Value. Permitted development rights do not apply for as long as the pub is nominated or listed as an Asset of Community Value, and a planning application is required for the change of use or demolition of the building. Any pub can be nominated as an Asset of Community Value.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-13T14:06:23.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670689/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670689/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670689/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-10","Public Houses: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will take steps to implement adequate permanent planning protections to help pubs to remain open; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","59274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670690","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-18","<p>Reforms to the New Homes Bonus have identified savings of £240m which will be made available for adult social care by means of a new, one-off, Adult Social Care Support Grant. This grant will be distributed to all social care authorities in accordance with the social care relative needs formula.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-18T17:38:15.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670690/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670690/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670690/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670690/answer/previousversion/29830","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-10","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 9 January 2017 to Question 58515, what plans he has to fund social care through new homes bonuses in two tier local authority areas; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen McPartland","Stevenage","Stephen McPartland","59298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670691","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-16","<p>My Department does not hold information about the number of official reminder letters issued by local authorities about payment of council tax.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-16T17:04:03.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670691/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670691/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670691/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670691/answer/previousversion/29833","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-10","Councillors: Council Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many local councillors have been sent official reminder letters for not paying council tax in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","59286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670692","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-24","<p>This Department welcomes the publication of the Each Home Counts Review and we will work with industry to understand how the sector proposes to implement the recommendations of the review.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-24T17:03:10.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670692/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670692/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670692/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-10","Consumer Advice, Protection, Standards and Enforcement for Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what his response is to the findings and recommendations of the Bonfield Review, Each Home Counts, December 2016.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","59319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670693","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-26","<p>The numbers of households on local authority waiting lists for each local authority in England since 1997 is published in live table 600 which is available here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-rents-lettings-and-tenancies" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-rents-lettings-and-tenancies</a></p><p>Figures are not available at constituency level.</p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-26T11:40:52.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670693/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670693/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670693/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-10","Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much was spent on housing in (a) Jarrow constituency, (b) South Tyneside, (c) the North East and (d) the UK in each year since 1997.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","59338"
