"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670751","Department for Education","false","2017-01-23","<p>Socially disadvantaged and hardest to reach learners may have no or few qualifications, complex lives with multiple problems or a diagnosed or undiagnosed learning difficulty and may require more support to engage in, and complete, their learning.</p><p> </p><p>FE providers work with a wide range of partners in their area to develop innovative ways of responding to the needs of disadvantaged learners. For many, engagement will be through non-accredited learning progressing to full qualifications, a traineeship, apprenticeship, or employment/self-employment.</p><p> </p><p>We do not hold data on courses designed to support people with a learning disability in Further Education Colleges.</p><p> </p><p><strong><br> </strong></p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-01-23T12:57:45.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670751/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670751/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670751/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-10","Further Education: Learning Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many courses designed to support people with a learning disability were provided in a further education college in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","59454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670752","Department for Education","false","2017-01-18","<p>Destinations of students six months after leaving UK higher education institutions (HEIs) are collected and published annually by the Higher Education Statistics Agency (HESA) as part of the Destination of Leavers from Higher Education (DLHE) survey. Statistics on the destinations of EU domiciled students six months after leaving UK HEIs, including the numbers in UK employment, are published in Table 1 of HESA’s Statistical First Release. The latest statistics were published in June 2016 for students leaving their courses in the 2014/15 academic year at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.hesa.ac.uk/news/30-06-2016/sfr237-destinations-of-leavers" target="_blank">https://www.hesa.ac.uk/news/30-06-2016/sfr237-destinations-of-leavers</a></p><p>The occupations of employed graduates are also recorded in the DLHE survey but a standard categorisation of these into science, technology, engineering and mathematics is not available.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-01-18T17:08:01.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670752/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670752/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670752/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-10","Graduates: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the number of EU graduate students who have remained in (a) the UK and (b) Scotland, employed in jobs relating to (i) science, (ii) technology, (iii) engineering and (iv) mathematics subject areas in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","59414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670753","Department for Education","false","2017-01-18","<p>The information requested is not available. Destinations of students six months after leaving UK higher education institutions (HEIs) are collected and published annually by the Higher Education Statistics Agency (HESA) as part of the Destination of Leavers from Higher Education (DLHE) survey. However, the location of residence of higher education leavers is not collected.</p><p>Latest statistics were published in June 2016 for students leaving their courses in the 2014/15 academic year and are available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.hesa.ac.uk/news/30-06-2016/sfr237-destinations-of-leavers" target="_blank">https://www.hesa.ac.uk/news/30-06-2016/sfr237-destinations-of-leavers</a></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-01-18T17:05:36.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670753/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670753/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670753/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-10","Graduates: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the number of EU students who have remained in (a) the UK and (b) Scotland after graduating with degrees in (i) science, (ii) technology, (iii) engineering and (iv) mathematics in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","59415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670754","Department for Education","false","2017-01-25","<p>The Gazelle College Group is an independent organisation, not funded by Government. Decisions taken by Colleges to join or fund independent sector bodies are for their Corporations as charitable trustees, who should ensure they receive value for money for any expenditure incurred.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-01-25T14:09:25.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670754/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670754/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670754/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-10","Further Education: Business","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what investigations (a) her Department and (b) the Further Education Commissioner has undertaken into the educational impact and value for money of the Gazelle Colleges Group, and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","59471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670755","Department for Education","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Secretary of State’s written ministerial statement to Parliament of 19 October set out that, while we intend to consult on the best starting point to measure the progress that children make at primary school, no new types of statutory assessment will be introduced in primary schools prior to the 2018-2019 academic year. We have also confirmed that the Early Years Foundation Stage Profile will remain in place for the 2016-2017 and 2017-2018 academic years.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-01-16T17:03:34.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670755/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670755/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670755/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-10","Primary Education: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when she plans to announce plans for primary school on-entry assessment in  2017; and if the assessment will give the different stages of brain development experienced by boys and girls during early years.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","59490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670756","Department for Education","false","2017-01-23","<p>The data in the National Pupil Database helps give us a clear picture of how the school system is working. The Department takes privacy extremely seriously and access to sensitive data is strictly controlled. Allowing vetted researchers and academics access to excerpts of this data, in an anonymised format and under strictly controlled conditions, can help the development and improvement of our education system for the benefit of all.</p><p>The applications accepted to extract information from the National Pupil Database over the past 5 years are detailed in the table below. These include both the Department’s and external requests.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total number of cases accepted </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>328</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>311</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>380</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>396</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>380</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-01-23T15:55:22.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670756/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670756/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670756/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-10","Pupils: Personal Records","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 10 January 2017 to Question 57722, how many applications to extract information from the National Pupil Database were accepted in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","59403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670757","Department for Education","false","2017-01-13","<p>The individual concerned was recruited to a temporary maternity cover role in the Skills Funding Agency on a one-year contract. The recruitment fell under Exception 1 of the Civil Service Commissioner’s recruitment principles which covers temporary appointments to fulfil an urgent need for specific skills.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-01-13T14:22:57.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670757/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670757/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670757/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-10","Maria Strizzolo","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the process was for Ms Maria Strizzolo's appointment to the Skills Funding Agency.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","59416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670758","Department for Education","false","2017-01-16","<p>We take the issue of witness anonymity extremely seriously.</p><p>The independent panel overseeing the teacher misconduct case of some of the individuals involved in the events related to Trojan Horse recently ordered the full disclosure of transcripts of interviews given to Peter Clarke. As a result of the independent panel’s direction, lawyers acting on behalf of NCTL wrote to witnesses to inform them of that decision, and stated that in the event that they had any comments or concerns in relation to the disclosure of their transcripts they should contact them. Since the direction, where we have written to witnesses and we have either not yet heard back from them or they have raised concerns, no disclosures have been made. We have informed the independent panel that a number of witnesses have raised concerns, and the panel has indicated that it wishes to consider the issue at a further hearing.</p><p>These issues are part of a set of complex legal proceedings and it would be inappropriate to comment further at this stage.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-01-16T17:39:22.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670758/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670758/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670758/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-10","Schools: Birmingham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to preserve the anonymity of witnesses who provided evidence to the Clarke inquiry into Birmingham schools.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","59378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670759","Department for Education","false","2017-01-25","<p>The report of the Sussex area review was published on 29 November 2016 and can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sussex-further-education-area-review-report" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sussex-further-education-area-review-report</a>. Copies of the draft report were sent to Hon members on the 23 June 2016, in advance of their meeting with officials to discuss the recommendations arising from the review prior to publication.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-01-25T14:05:47.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670759/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670759/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670759/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-10","Further Education: Sussex","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, on what exact date the Sussex Area Review was published; and on what date copies of that review were sent to hon. Members.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","59406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670760","Department for Education","false","2017-01-18","<p>We want to ensure that everyone with the potential has the opportunity to benefit from higher education, regardless of their background. In our most recent Guidance to the Director of Fair Access, we asked him to focus universities on increasing the participation of white, working-class boys in higher education.</p><p>We are also legislating to introduce a Transparency Duty on institutions which would require them to publish application, offer and drop-out rates by socio-economic background, ethnicity and gender. Other measures in the Higher Education and Research Bill focusing on widening participation by under-represented groups include:</p><p>o bringing together Office for Fair Access (OFFA) and Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE) resources and expertise in the proposed Office for Students (OfS) to rationalise and improve delivery;</p><p>o ensuring access and participation plans explicitly cover access, progression and student success; placing an overarching duty on the OfS to have regard to the need to promote equality of opportunity in relation to access and participation in all that it does; and</p><p>o ensuring the Director for Fair Access and Participation has a clear role within the OfS in relation to access and participation activities.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-01-18T17:28:16.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670760/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670760/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670760/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-10","Higher Education: Males","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that working class, white males are better able to access higher education.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","59364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670761","Department for Education","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Department has recently made £50m available through the Early Years Capital Fund, which was a bid round committed to creating new 30 hours places and was open to local authorities, working in partnership with providers (this included providers that currently offer, or plan to offer, provision for 3- and 4-year olds) in their area. This one-off bidding round closed at the end of August 2016 and we published outcomes in January 2017.</p><p>All local authorities were informed of the status of their projects in December 2016 and a full list of successful projects can be found at: www.gov.uk/guidance/early-years-capital-fund-2017</p><p>We will publish individual project amounts in due course as to do so now would inhibit local authorities’ negotiations with suppliers and their ability to secure value for money.</p><p>Also attached is a document containing a list of the 510 projects originally submitted by local authorities.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-01-13T11:40:20.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670761/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670761/answer","59327 attachment -  510 local authority submitted projects.xlsx","List of 510 projecs submitted by local authoritie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670761/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-10","Pre-school Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, further to her Department's £50 million funding announcement for early years capital projects of 10 January 2017, (a) how much each funded project will receive, (b) how much funding has been granted to projects in each local authority area in England and (c) how many applications for funding were received to support projects in each local authority area.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","59327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670762","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-17","<p>Under the provisons of Article 4.(b)(i) of EC CITES Regulation 338/97 it is a requirement that an export permit is issued by the CITES Management Authority of the country exporting the specimen, and is presented before the UK CITES Management Authority issues an import permit.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-17T12:35:48.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670762/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670762/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670762/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-10","Lions: Hunting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 13 December 2016 to Question 56691, what steps her Department has taken to identify the (a) country of origin of the lion trophies identified and (b) country that exported those trophies in 2015.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","59271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670763","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-17","<p>Defra is continuing to look carefully at the issue of lion hunting and trophy imports.</p><p> </p><p>At the 17<sup>th</sup> meeting of the Conference of the Parties to the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) in September 2016, which I attended, Parties agreed to remove a loophole allowing hunting trophies to be transported as personal effects. Parties also agreed clear criteria which the exporting country should consider when assessing that the hunt was both legal and sustainable before issuing an export permit.</p><p> </p><p>In the case of lions, the UK has to then confirm that we agree with this assessment and issue a corresponding import permit before any import can take place. As part of this process, the UK’s scientific advisors for fauna, the Joint Nature Conservation Committee, considers whether the import would be harmful to the conservation of the species or the extent of its range, taking into account available scientific evidence. An import permit is only issued if the trade is not considered to be detrimental to the survival of the species in the wild.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-17T10:27:10.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670763/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670763/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670763/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-10","Lions: Hunting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 27 June 2016 to Question 40644, what recent assessment she has made of improvements in the way lion hunting takes place; what criteria are used to measure such improvements; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","59331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670764","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-18","<p>Adaptation is embedded as an integral part of policy making across Defra and all levels of Government, and within a broad range of programmes and activities that directly or indirectly support and build the UK’s resilience to climate change. It is, therefore, not possible to provide an estimate of the total amount of resource applied to support our National Adaptation Programme objectives across all of those policies, programmes and activities.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-18T11:39:46.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670764/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670764/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670764/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-10","Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what financial resources her Department has allocated for the UK National Adaption programme; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","59303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670765","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-18","<p>Exiting the EU gives us an unprecedented opportunity to design a domestic agriculture policy fit for the 21st century, reducing the regulatory burden on agricultural businesses, and supporting resilience and growth.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-01-18T11:38:43.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670765/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670765/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670765/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-10","Agriculture: Profits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate she has made of the potential effect of the UK exiting the EU on the profitability of farmers and growers in the UK; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","59301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670766","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-18","<p>Defra holds an animal health research budget of around £15m in 2016/17 of which around £0.5m specifically relates to a new and emerging disease sub-programme. Defra holds a plant health research budget of around £4m in 2016/17 which is prioritised according to threats listed in the plant health risk register. The exact size of future research investment is not confirmed and will be dependent on the nature and extent of future risks.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-01-18T17:45:25.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670766/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670766/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670766/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-10","Pests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what resources her Department has allocated for research into new and emerging pests and diseases in each of the next five years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","59302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670767","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-18","<p>Defra has supported a range of research relevant to improving understanding of the effects of neonicotinoids (and other pesticides on bees). Recently completed work includes studies on: quantifying the exposure of bumblebees to neonicotinoids and mixtures of pesticides (commenced 2013); interpreting pesticide residues in honeybees (published 2015); using radio-frequency identification devices to assess effects of pesticides on foraging bees (commenced 2013); and protection goals for bee colonies (commenced 2015).</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-01-18T11:37:53.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670767/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670767/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670767/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-10","Neonicotinoids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what studies her Department is carrying out on neonicotinoid pesticides; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","59300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670768","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-18","<p>The Government is considering next steps on a review of the intra-UK allocation of the CAP budget. An update will be provided shortly.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-01-18T11:39:18.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670768/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670768/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670768/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-10","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans she has to review the disbursement of payments from the convergence uplift scheme.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","59375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670769","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-13","<p>Calculations for the Soil Moisture Deficit (SMD) on the last day of each month from October 2016 are set out in the table below in millimetres:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>County</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>31 October 2016</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>30 November 2016</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>31 December 2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(a) Kent</p></td><td><p>96.4</p></td><td><p>31.0</p></td><td><p>26.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(b) Essex</p></td><td><p>96.8</p></td><td><p>42.1</p></td><td><p>38.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(c) Hertfordshire</p></td><td><p>97.8</p></td><td><p>30.1</p></td><td><p>23.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(d) Hampshire</p></td><td><p>98.9</p></td><td><p>33.2</p></td><td><p>23.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(e) Bedfordshire</p></td><td><p>93.3</p></td><td><p>27.6</p></td><td><p>13.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(f) Surrey</p></td><td><p>92.4</p></td><td><p>25.0</p></td><td><p>19.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(g) East Sussex</p></td><td><p>112.5</p></td><td><p>26.2</p></td><td><p>15.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(h) West Sussex</p></td><td><p>84.7</p></td><td><p>20.6</p></td><td><p>12.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(i) Wiltshire</p></td><td><p>70.2</p></td><td><p>11.4</p></td><td><p>6.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(j) Dorset</p></td><td><p>65.5</p></td><td><p>9.4</p></td><td><p>2.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(k) Buckinghamshire</p></td><td><p>100.7</p></td><td><p>29.3</p></td><td><p>18.7</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>The figures apply to real land use (e.g. proportions of urban, grass or crops) and for a soil with water holding capacity at the median level for the soils in each county. SMD is produced on 40km squares; for this purpose they have been weighted to produce a county average according to the percentage of each square that lies within each county. The data presented comes from the Met Office Rainfall and Evaporation Calculation System (MORECS).</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-01-13T11:56:02.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670769/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670769/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670769/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-10","Soil: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what soil moisture levels were in each month from October 2016 in (a) Kent, (b) Essex, (c) Hertfordshire, (d) Hampshire, (e) Bedfordshire, (f) Surrey, (g) East Sussex, (h) West Sussex, (i) Wiltshire, (j) Dorset and (k) Buckinghamshire; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker","59482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670770","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-23","<p>We do not publish information on investigations undertaken by Defra Investigation Services given the confidential nature of such enquiries. However, we are considering an FOI request regarding the subsequent review that was carried out on the original investigation referred to by my Honourable Friend.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-01-23T14:39:55.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670770/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670770/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670770/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-10","Horses: Dartmoor National Park","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will publish the conclusions of her Department's investigations into the use of contraceptives for Dartmoor ponies.","false","Biography information for Mr Geoffrey Cox","Torridge and West Devon","Mr Geoffrey Cox","59484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670771","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-18","<p>The UK fully supported a UN resolution tabled in the Security Council by the US in response to the Secretary General's report. This draft resolution called for an arms embargo and targeted sanctions against those responsible for the continued violence. We lobbied hard, both in New York and in the appropriate capitals, but disappointingly the resolution was not adopted. We continue to work closely with the region and the wider international community to mitigate the risks identified in the Secretary General's report.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-18T15:39:07.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670771/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670771/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670771/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-10","South Sudan: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the statement made by the Secretary General of the United Nations on 19 December 2017 on the situation in South Sudan, what steps he has taken in response to concerns on potential genocide in that country.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","59480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670772","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union is working closely across government to assess the potential impact on UK nationals living and working in other EU Member States. We recognise their concerns.</p><p><strong><br></strong>The Prime Minister has been clear that the Government will seek an early agreement to protect the status of UK citizens living in EU Member States, in the same way that we want to protect the status of EU nationals already living in the UK.<strong><br></strong></p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-01-13T13:27:19.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670772/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670772/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670772/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-10","British Nationals Abroad: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has made of the implication for the Government's policies of changes to the residency rights of UK nationals living and working in other EU Member States.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","59446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670773","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-17","<p><em>​</em>There is no observer status or associate membership of the Commonwealth of Nations. The criteria for membership include the requirement to be a full sovereign state, and Somaliland is not internationally recognised. HMG's position has long been that it is for Somalia and Somaliland to decide their future, and for regional neighbours to take the lead in recognising any new arrangements.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-17T16:07:28.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670773/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670773/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670773/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-10","Somaliland: Commonwealth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what his Department's policy is on the bidding by Somaliland for Observer Status of the Commonwealth of Nations.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","59373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670774","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-13","<p>​It has long been our position that Israeli settlement activity is illegal and undermines the viability of two states for two peoples, but it is far from the only obstacle to peace. UN Security Council Resolution 2334 addresses settlements while also calling for an end to incitement and terror. The resolution passed on 23 December and asks the Secretary-General to report to the Council every three months on the implementation of its provisions. We will monitor the situation closely.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-13T13:35:36.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670774/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670774/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670774/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-10","Israeli Settlements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of Israeli compliance with United Nations Security Council Resolution 2334 (2016) on urging an end to Israeli settlements.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","59409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670775","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>The UK's Arctic Policy Framework, Adapting to Change: UK Policy towards the Arctic, was compiled by the Foreign &amp; Commonwealth Office (FCO), with input on specific areas of policy from each relevant Whitehall Department. Policy Departments are responsible for engaging the Devolved Administrations, as appropriate. However, in developing a revised framework, to be published later this year, the FCO has also opened a direct dialogue with the Scottish Government.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-16T17:24:21.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670775/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670775/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670775/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-10","Arctic: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions took place with the Scottish Government before the publication of the document, Adapting to Change: UK Policy towards the Arctic in October 2013.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","59382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670776","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-17","<p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson) met the Israeli Ambassador to London in Jerusalem on 30 September.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-17T16:05:01.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670776/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670776/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670776/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-10","Israel: Diplomatic Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many meetings he has had with Israeli embassy officials since taking office.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","59358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670777","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-17","<p>The special advisers to the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson) did not have any meetings with Israeli Embassy officials during 2016.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-17T15:58:54.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670777/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670777/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670777/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-10","Israel: Diplomatic Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many meetings Government special advisers had with Israeli embassy officials in 2016.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","59355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670778","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-17","<p>The Israeli ambassador has apologised and been clear these comments do not reflect the views of the embassy or Government of Israel. The UK has a strong relationship with Israel and we consider the matter closed.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-17T16:01:34.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670778/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670778/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670778/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-10","Israel: Diplomatic Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the Israeli authorities as a result of recently reported comments made by an Israeli diplomat in respect of a Government Minister.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","59356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670779","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-17","<p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson) has not had any face-to-face meetings with Conservative Friends of Israel since taking office, but did speak at an event organised by Conservative Friends of Israel during the Conservative Party Conference in October 2016.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-17T16:03:31.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670779/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670779/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670779/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-10","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Conservative Friends of Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many meetings he has had with representatives of the Conservative Friends of Israel since taking office.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","59357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670780","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>Foreign Office officials recently met Scottish Government officials to exchange views on the UK's Arctic Policy Framework and Scotland's interests in the region.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-16T17:22:42.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670780/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670780/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670780/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-10","Arctic: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with the Scottish Government on the contribution Scotland could make to the UK's policy on the Arctic.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","59380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670781","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>As a State Observer, the British Government monitors all of the Arctic Council's working groups and task forces, contributing to those on which the UK can have a genuine impact. The UK contributes to the work of the Protection of the Arctic Marine Environment, Conservation of Arctic Flora and Fauna and the Arctic Monitoring Assessment Programme (AMAP) working groups.</p><p>UK attendance is by both Government officials and non-Governmental experts, depending on the nature of the meeting and the desired UK input. Foreign Office officials, representatives from the Joint Nature Conservation Committee, the Plymouth Marine Laboratory and the British Antarctic Survey have all attended recent meetings.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-16T17:21:44.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670781/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670781/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670781/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-10","Arctic Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, to how many of the Arctic Council working groups the UK contributes; and who attends each such working group as the UK's representatives.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","59313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670782","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>The UK has participated in all Ministerial and Senior Arctic Officials meetings of the Arctic Council held in the last five years.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-16T17:19:56.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670782/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670782/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670782/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-10","Arctic Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many Arctic Council meetings the UK has participated in during the last five years.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","59314"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670783","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-17","<p>Alongside continued discussion with the Government of Iraq, Ministers and officials have ongoing discussions regarding the campaign to bring Daesh to justice with European counterparts, both in Brussels and in capitals. The campaign seeks to offer support to all Daesh's victims, including Yezidis who have been subject to horrific violence at the hands of Daesh.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-17T16:09:57.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670783/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670783/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670783/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-10","Yazidis: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his European counterparts on providing support for Yazidi women who have escaped captivity by ISIS.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","59392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670784","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-17","<p>The UK decided to attend the Paris Conference only as an observer and, in that capacity, we did not sign up to the Communiqué. Britain welcomes France's efforts to promote peace but we have been clear for some time that a conference so close to the change of US administration, and without the attendance of the two main parties, would not be the best way to make real progress on this complex issue.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-17T15:56:20.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670784/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670784/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670784/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-10","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will attend the Paris conference on Israel and the Occupied Palestinian Territories in January 2017.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","59347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670785","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office regularly reviews the suitability of its premises overseas, including those it shares with other countries and international organisations.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-16T17:41:08.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670785/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670785/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670785/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-10","Diplomatic Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 22 December 2016 to Question 57858, what discussions he has had with his counterparts in the European Council about continuing to share diplomatic premises with EU institutions.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","59321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670786","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-17","<p>We work very closely with the US and Norway (our Troika partners) and other key international actors in support of the peace process. The UK Special Representative for Sudan and South Sudan is in contact with his US and Norwegian counterparts at least once a week to ensure that our efforts to support the peace process are coordinated effectively, as part of our extensive bilateral and multilateral engagement with international and regional partners at both ministerial and official level.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-17T15:47:25.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670786/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670786/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670786/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-10","South Sudan: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterparts in the Troika on support for the peace process in South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","59276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670787","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-17","<p>​During my visit to Juba I met President Kiir, senior officials from the South Sudanese Government and civil society representatives, directly raising our concerns whilst also reiterating our support to the South Sudanese people. The majority of the South Sudanese opposition leaders are currently outside of the country; we maintain regular engagement with them through the UK Special Representative for Sudan and South Sudan.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-17T15:54:27.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670787/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670787/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670787/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-10","South Sudan: Visits Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions the Minister for Africa and the Middle East had with opposition leaders during his recent visit to South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","59283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670788","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-17","<p>Ministers and senior officials regularly raise human rights concerns with the Egyptian authorities, including the restrictions on civil society.</p><p>The Prime Minister raised the ongoing 'Foreign Funding' NGO case with President Sisi when they last met on 20 September. She stressed the importance of NGOs being able to operate in Egypt. I made a statement on the reopening of the case in March, and I and senior officials have raised it with the Egyptian authorities on several occasions.</p><p>Following the Egyptian Parliament's passing of the draft Non-Governmental Organisations (NGO) Law on 29 November, I made a statement (available on the gov.uk website) on 1 December and 13 January expressing our concern with the draft law and the restrictions it will enforce on civil society. Senior officials and I have raised concerns about the NGO law with the Egyptian Government and Parliament in private on a number of occasions. Senior officials raised this most recently on 11 January.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-17T15:52:36.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670788/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670788/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670788/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-10","Egypt: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government has taken to address restrictions on civil society in Egypt.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","59254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670789","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-17","<p>We continue to call on the Palestinian leadership to work towards genuine and democratic elections for all Palestinians. Strong, inclusive and democratic institutions, based on respect of the rule of law and human rights, are crucial elements in establishing a viable and sovereign Palestinian State. Our Consulate General in Jerusalem has regularly discussed the local elections with senior Palestinian ministers and officials over the past months. Following the postponement of the elections, we have continued to urge all sides to make efforts to hold genuine and democratic local elections in the West Bank and Gaza in accordance with the law.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-17T15:37:35.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670789/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670789/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670789/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-10","Gaza and West Bank: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to support free and fair elections in the West Bank and Gaza.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","59251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670790","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-17","<p>We are deeply concerned about the treatment of the LGBT community in the Occupied Palestinian Territories (OPTs), particularly in Gaza where they are subject to widespread social discrimination for cultural and religious reasons. Homosexuality remains a taboo subject in the OPTs. In some places, such as Ramallah, these taboos are relaxed, but in more conservative areas the situation is very challenging. There are no laws protecting LGBT people, although we are not aware of any recent legal cases targeting the LGBT community.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-17T15:39:45.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670790/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670790/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670790/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-10","Palestinians: LGBT People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on the Palestinian Authority's commitment to equality for LGBT people in the Palestinian territories; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","59252"
