"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670799","Department of Health","false","2017-01-13","<p>No recent representations have been received from National Health Service trusts in respect of additional support for accident and emergency services in England.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-13T12:05:32.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670799/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670799/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670799/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-10","Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent representations he has received from NHS trusts requesting additional support for accident and emergency services in England; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","59328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670800","Department of Health","false","2017-01-18","<p>We do not have a record of any complaints, concerning transfer of patient records, made against the West Yorkshire Central Services Agency in this period.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-18T11:58:15.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670800/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670800/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670800/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-10","West Yorkshire Central Services Agency: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many complaints were made against West Yorkshire Central Services about the transfer of patient records in each month from 1 September 2014 to 31 August 2015.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","59305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670801","Department of Health","false","2017-01-18","<p>No such estimate has been made. We expect clinicians to consider the cost of a medicine in making prescribing decisions but recognise that there may be valid reasons why the prescribing of a higher cost product may sometimes be appropriate to meet the clinical needs of individual patients. The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence supports clinically and cost effective prescribing through the production of evidence-based guidance for healthcare professionals.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-18T11:36:31.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670801/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670801/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670801/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-10","Prescriptions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of potential savings to the NHS budget of prescribing the most cost-effective inhaler medication to each NHS patient.","false","Biography information for Stephen McPartland","Stevenage","Stephen McPartland","59312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670802","Department of Health","false","2017-01-18","<p>Neither Ministers nor officials have had any such discussions with the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE). Officials have had contact with Roche about its patient access scheme proposals for trastuzumab emtansine since the consultation on NICE’s draft guidance opened on 20 December 2016.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-18T11:49:47.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670802/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670802/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670802/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-10","Breast Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions his Department has had with (a) the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence and (b) Roche on draft guidance on Kadcyla (trastuzumab emtansine) during the consultation period.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","59317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670803","Department of Health","false","2017-01-13","<p>We are informed by NHS England that the contract for 'core services' which will be let by NHS Liverpool Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) on behalf of the CCG, Liverpool City Council and NHS England has not yet been let. Following a transaction process led by NHS Improvement (NHSI), Bridgewater NHS Foundation Trust (FT) has been identified as the preferred bidder, and the submission is being assured by NHSI. When let, the existing Liverpool Community Health contract will novate to Bridgewater NHS FT. As such, and as with all other major National Health Service contracts, there is no specific end point.</p><p> </p><p>The accepted bid for 2017/18 includes £4.6 million non-recurrent funding for transition and transformation, the same level as for the current year.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-13T14:53:07.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670803/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670803/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670803/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-10","Community Health Services: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 9 January 2017 to Questions 58635, 58636, 58637, 58638, 58639, whether there is any non-recurrent funding in the contract let by Liverpool Clinical Commissioning Group for Liverpool community health services to be provided by Bridgewater Community Healthcare NHS Foundation Trust from 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","59411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670804","Department of Health","false","2017-01-13","<p>We are informed by NHS England that the contract for 'core services' which will be let by NHS Liverpool Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) on behalf of the CCG, Liverpool City Council and NHS England has not yet been let. Following a transaction process led by NHS Improvement (NHSI), Bridgewater NHS Foundation Trust (FT) has been identified as the preferred bidder, and the submission is being assured by NHSI. When let, the existing Liverpool Community Health NHS Trust contract will novate to Bridgewater NHS FT. As such, and as with all other major National Health Service contracts, there is no specific end point.</p><p> </p><p>The accepted bid for 2017/18 is for £77 million recurrent funding, the same level as for the current year.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-13T14:50:04.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670804/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670804/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670804/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-10","Community Health Services: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 9 January 2017 to Questions 58635, 58636, 58637, 58638, 58639, what the recurrent contract value is in the contract let by Liverpool Clinical Commissioning Group for Liverpool community health services to be provided by Bridgewater Community Healthcare NHS Foundation Trust from 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","59412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670805","Department of Health","false","2017-01-18","<p>We have made no such assessment.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has advised that it has carefully translated the evidence base on which the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has based its recommendations of clinical and cost effectiveness into practical clarifications which directly relate to how the recommended drug combinations are incorporated into known treatment pathways in use in England. It has advised that each set of such clarifications is in keeping with the NICE recommendations.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-18T11:46:37.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670805/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670805/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670805/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-10","Skin Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effect of restrictions imposed by NHS England on the use of the (a) dabrafenib plus trametinib and (b) ipilimumab plus nivolumab drug combinations for use in the treatment of advanced melanoma on patient care.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","59488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670806","Department of Health","false","2017-01-13","<p>We are informed by NHS England that the contract for 'core services' which will be let by NHS Liverpool Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) on behalf of the CCG, Liverpool City Council and NHS England has not yet been let. Following a transaction process led by NHS Improvement (NHSI), Bridgewater NHS FT has been identified as the preferred bidder, and the submission is being assured by NHSI. When let, the existing Liverpool Community Health contract will novate to Bridgewater NHS FT. As such, and as with all other major National Health Service contracts, there is no specific end point.</p><p> </p><p>Bidders were told prior to re-submitting their bids in August 2016 for the first two years, that non-recurrent resource would reduce over a period of time.</p><p>Contract values for 2019/20, 2020/21 and 2021/22 will be negotiated and agreed in advance of those financial years. As such, no figure can be put on depreciation over a future five year period by commissioners.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-13T15:04:39.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670806/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670806/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670806/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-10","Community Health Services: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 9 January 2017 to Questions 58635, 58636, 58637, 58638, 58639, what the depreciation value is of the recurrent contract value let by Liverpool Clinical Commissioning Group for Liverpool community health services over five years in the Bridgewater Community Healthcare NHS Foundation Trust financial plan for community health services in Liverpool.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","59410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670807","Department of Health","false","2017-01-13","<p>We are informed by NHS England that the contract for 'core services' which will be let by NHS Liverpool Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) on behalf of the CCG, Liverpool City Council and NHS England has not yet been let. Following a transaction process led by NHS Improvement (NHSI), Bridgewater NHS Foundation Trust (FT) has been identified as the preferred bidder, and the submission is being assured by NHSI. When let, the existing Liverpool Community Health NHS Trust contract will novate to Bridgewater NHS FT. As such, and as with all other major National Health Service contracts, there is no specific end point.</p><p> </p><p>Efficiency targets post 2018/19 cannot be forecast for any NHS provider. For 2017/18 and 2018/19, all NHS providers are expected to deliver the nationally set target of 2% efficiencies. This would be expected of Bridgewater NHS FT across all its services.</p><p> </p><p>The Cheshire and Mersey Sustainability and Transformation Plan (STP) contained a national template which set out that community spend was anticipated to increase by approximately 3.5% per year (for all CCGs) while hospital spend was anticipated to increase by approximately 1.8% each year. The STP, along with other planning activity, is expected to manage spend to sustainable levels while also ensuring quality and service performance are secured. In North Mersey, there is a Local Delivery System Plan which describes all the work to be undertaken to address this. This includes implementation of the Healthy Liverpool Community Model.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-13T15:00:03.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670807/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670807/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670807/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-10","Community Health Services: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 9 January 2017 to Questions 58635, 58636, 58637, 58638, 58639, whether the recurrent and non-recurrent contract value let by Liverpool Clinical Commissioning Group for Liverpool community health services includes (a) the National annual two per cent NHS Efficiency target and (b) the North Mersey Sustainability and Transformation Plan requirement for an annual 3.5 per cent increase in community health service case activity in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","59413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670808","Department of Health","false","2017-01-18","<p>This is a matter for Wirral Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) and NHS England. We understand these bodies have agreed that the forecast outturn deficit for Wirral CCG would increase from £9 million to £12 million in the Month 9 national submission.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-18T15:04:29.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670808/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670808/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670808/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-10","Wirral Clinical Commissioning Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to Wirral Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) Board Papers, published on 10 January 2017, for what reasons NHS England have asked the CCG not to adjust their deficit forecast from £9.028 million to £11.989 million.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","59478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670809","Department of Health","false","2017-01-18","<p>Funding is not allocated by the Department on a regional basis. Overall spending limits are agreed with NHS England and other arm’s length bodies on an annual basis.</p><p>National Health Service trusts are not funded directly by the Department. They are semi-autonomous organisations who fund their activity via income derived from the provision of services to commissioners.</p><p>Income levels are agreed between local commissioners and providers based on levels of activity within local health economy which are inherently volatile from year to year.</p><p>The Department reports total spending incurred each year by bodies within the departmental group for England, in its Annual Report and Accounts. The 2015-16 Department of Health Annual Report and Accounts can be found on the Department’s website via the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/539602/DH_Annual_Report_Web.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/539602/DH_Annual_Report_Web.pdf</a></p><p>Total departmental spending outturns from 2007-08 to 2015-16 can be found on page 178, annex A, Core Table 1.</p><p>Spending in the rest of the United Kingdom are a matter for the devolved administrations.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-18T16:52:40.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670809/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670809/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670809/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-10","Health Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much NHS funding has been allocated to (a) South Tyneside, (b) the North East and (c) the UK in each year since 1997.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","59365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670810","Department of Health","false","2017-01-13","<p>The information is not available in the format requested.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-13T10:42:35.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670810/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670810/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670810/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-10","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of people with severe mental health problems received screening in accordance with NICE guidelines in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","59430"
